picks up 6th graf pvs, ``Bentsen arrived xxx''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said he thought he `` did fine'' in Wednesday night's vice presidential debate, and that Republican opponent <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> did not adequately explain what he would do if he suddenly became president. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> received a telephone call from Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> immediately after the debate, then left for a rally at a nearby hotel. There, the Democratic vice presidential nominee was cheered by 700 supporters. A large sign declared, `` And the winner is <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>.'' Asked if he thought he had won the debate, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said, `` I think I did fine, and I enjoyed it. I had fun. I think we made our points.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> referred to the repeated questioning of <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> about the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> vice presidential nominee's qualifications to assume the presidency. `` I stood up there for 90 minutes listening to Senator <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> say what he was going to do if he was president of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and I still did n't know. Finally I realized all he was going to do was go back to that script again,'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> called <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> to wish him well before the debate. The Democratic ticket planned a reunion Thursday at a steel plant rally near <LOCATION> Longview </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> on Tuesday night after four days of intense preparations, first in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and then in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. He took time to spend with his wife and three children and planned to work out in the hotel gym to help him relax before the debate. B.A. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> accompanied her husband to the private tour of the debate site Wednesday afternoon. Afterward, according to press secretary <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, 67, picked up his wife and carried her off the stage. `` She looked like she was willing to go with him anywhere,'' he said. Much of his preparation was devoted to making <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> comfortable with the format of the debate, which limited the candidates to two-minute answers and one-minute responses, aides said. `` It's a matter of taking the language of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and putting it in a form that's suitable for television,'' <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON> said. Although his advisers admitted helping <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> `` frame his answers,'' <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON> said, `` we have not armed him with a lot of cute one-liners. That's not really his style.'' `` I think we'll leave the one-liners to <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailes </PERSON> and <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aide <PERSON> Leslie </PERSON> <PERSON> Dach </PERSON>, referring to the Republican media strategist who has been coaching the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> candidate. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and other Democrats have tried to exploit public uneasiness about <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s qualifications for the job, and public polls show <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> is a drag on the Republican ticket. A strong performance by the 41-year-old <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> could turn that around. `` I do n't think people are going to judge this just by the fact he does n't stumble,'' <PERSON> Dach </PERSON> said. He said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> needed `` an extremely strong performance'' to overcome the public's doubts.
