<HEAD>Reaction Typically Partisan to Vice Presidential Debate</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republicans declared that <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> exceeded expectations in the vice presidential debate Wednesday night, while Democrats said the confrontation demonstrated <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s experience and qualifications for president As expected, reaction to the 90-minute debate held in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Neb. </LOCATION>, and broadcast nationally, was strongly partisan, with backers of Republican <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> praising <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s performance, and supporters of Democrat <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, declaring <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> the victor. White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> described President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> as `` gratified'' by the outcome and said the president called <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> to congratulate him. Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> said, `` Neither scored a knockout, but <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> looked and sounded more presidential.'' `` I do n't think there's any question <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> made himself an asset to the ticket tonight,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> McConnell </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, a national co-chairman of the <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign. `` Prior to tonight he was not.'' <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s jibe at <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> when the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator compared his experience to that of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> drew a mixed reaction. `` <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was a friend of mine,'' the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrat told <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. `` Senator, you're no <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.'' `` That was uncalled for, senator,'' retorted <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. `` It threw a chill over the whole debate, a sour note,'' said Atlanta-based pollster <PERSON> Clairbourne </PERSON> <PERSON> Darden </PERSON>. `` It changed from then on, the way you looked at <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>.'' But Democrats said <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> looked bad when he tried to compare himself with <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>. `` I think <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s worst moment was when he tried to cpmpare himself to <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>,'' said Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON> of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. `` He -LRB- <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> -RRB- was forced to think for himself and it did n't go over,'' said Sen. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Gore </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, D-Tenn. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Teichner </PERSON>, a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> pollster, said he saw no clear winner `` Because of the low expectations for <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, the polls will probably show that <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> probably won,'' said <PERSON> Teichner </PERSON>. `` As for whether the debate will help in the overall race, I think it's a wash.'' <PERSON> Merle </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, a political scientist at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` I think <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> did a better job I think the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> ticket ought to be helped by his performance.'' But he also praised <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> who, he said, `` performed well enough that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign will not have to engage in extensive damage control after tonight. But I think he was out-debated by <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Neuman </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> League