Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> had made `` absolutely no response to the fact that <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is simply out of step with mainstream <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' `` After tonight, <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> has a little better picture of the road that we want to take right into the 21st Century,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. As he was leaving the rally to head for his hotel room, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> was asked by reporters about <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s comment during the debate that `` You're no <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.'' `` It was uncalled for,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. Before the debate, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, in a jocular mood, had admonished the press to `` Watch us carefully. Take good notes. Good news stories now.'' `` I feel good,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said as he left his hotel for the debate. Earlier Wednesday, the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator, wearing makeup for his morning rehearsal before the cameras and tour of the Civic Auditorium stage with his top aides, looked confident and relaxed. `` We're ready,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told reporters as he emerged from his hotel. Asked if he was nervous, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> replied, `` Not yet.'' `` The mike works. That's very important to make sure the mike works and ours is working well,' he said as he left the debate hall. As for <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, his Democratic counterpart, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> joked, `` I just hope he shows up.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> had a low-key day as he prepared for the debate. He spent the afternoon relaxing in his hotel room, except for a brief walk outside. When reporters asked about his debate strategy, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said, `` We do n't want to give any strategies