<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here are excerpts from Wednesday night's debate between vice presidential candidates Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and Sen. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, R-Ind
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 Question: Why do you think that you have not made a more substantial impression on some of these people who have been able to observe you up close? Quayle: ... Qualifications for the office of vice president or president are not age alone ... Let's look at the three biggest issues that are going to be confronting <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> in the next presidency. Those three issues are national security and arms control, jobs and education, and the federal budget deficit. On each one of those issues I have more experience than does the governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>. ... <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>: This debate tonight, is not about the qualifications for the vice presidency. No, the debate tonight, is a debate about the presidency itself, and a presidential decision that has to be made by you. The stakes could not be higher. Question: If you had to step in to the presidency, who's agenda would you pursue? Yours, or -LRB- <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' -RRB-? <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>: ... We agree on so many things, and the vast majority of the issues. We agree on the fact that we have to cut this deficit ... Governor <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and I agree that we ought to have a trade policy for this country, that we've seen this administration more than double the national debt, that they've moved this country from the No. 1 lender nation in the world to the No. 1 debtor nation in the world under their administration, that they have not had a trade policy, that they've let trade be a handmaiden for the foreign policy objectives of the country, that this country has exported too many jobs and not enough products. ... Quayle: ... Governor <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, one of the most liberal governors in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, ... raised taxes five times. He just raised taxes this last year, and that's why a lot of people refer to him `` Tax Hike <PERSON> Mike </PERSON>.'' That's why they refer to the state of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> as Taxachusetts. ... Question: ... Are n't you and Gov. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> using -LRB- Social Security -RRB- politically, rather than dealing with it responsibily? <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>: ... We have a contract with the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people on Social Security, and <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> is an issue where Sen. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> voted eight times to cut the benefits on Social Security. ... Now, when you talk about Social Security the people that are going to protect it are the Democrats who brought forth that program. ... Quayle: Sen. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, you know that I did not vote to cut Social Security benefits eight times. What I have voted for, and what Sen. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> has voted for, is to delay the cost-of-living adjustments. ... You're right, they use this for political advantage. What they try to do time and time again is to scare the old people of this country. ... Question: ... Do you consider yourself an environmentalist? And, if you do, how do you reconcile that with your voting record? Quayle: I have a very strong record on the environment in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. ... I have voted for the major pieces of environmental legislation that have come down and been voted on in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>. ... If you bring up the environment, you ca n't help but think about the environmental policy of the governor of <LOCATION> Massachsetts </LOCATION>. ... The <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> which is the dirtiest waterway in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. ... What has the governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> done about that? Virtually nothing. ... <PERSON> B