<FIRST>r i PM-GulfMines     10-05 0573</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Gulf Mines,0587</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mine Threat Serious But Ignored, Military Sources Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Wednesday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD PYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Governments with a stake in the oil-rich <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> should give urgent priority to the threat from mines, Western military and diplomatic officials say. Even though there is a cease-fire in the Iran-Iraq war, `` the mines do n't know there's a cease-fire,'' said <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> Capt. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, who has commanded the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mine-sweeping contingent in the gulf for the past few months, said Monday, `` They're out there, cocked and ready to fire. If we do n't deal with them on our terms, we'll have to deal with them on theirs.'' At least seven mines have been found in the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> since the truce went into effect 45 days ago, and military sources speak of a `` statistical probability'' that a ship will hit one of the explosives. American intelligence assessments say there are 150 to 200 mines still in the gulf, concentrated in the north. Most are believed to have been laid by <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and some by <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, officers say, but neither country has provided data on the locations. These officers have predicted that the problem will worsen as winter storms cause more of the long-submerged explosives to break loose and follow prevailing currents down the western coast of the gulf. Military sources, speaking on condition they not be identified, said the mines threaten not only shipping but the fishing industry, underwater oil pipelines and children who sometimes find the odd-looking globes washed up on beaches. Several coastal fishing dhows have been sunk or damaged by mines. One source recalled that two <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION> children were killed by a mine last year, and said another was found recently in <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>. Between 12 and 50 mines are known to have been sunk, unexploded, by local naval units off the coast between <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>, one source said. `` If those are n't found and destroyed, one of them bumping against a pipeline and exploding could create an immense pollution problem,'' he said. Progress toward a coordinated effort to clear the mines is impeded by political concerns within the six-member <ORGANIZATION> Gulf </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cooperation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, the military and diplomatic sources said. The countries _ <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Qatar </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Oman </LOCATION> _ remained nominally neutral during the war but supported <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> against non-Arab <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Now, say Western diplomats, the council states are reluctant to undertake any action that either <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> might interpret as hostile. `` As long as the <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> peace talks remain stalled, nobody wants to do anything that could be seen as ` anti-anybody,' said one diplomat. The mine threat, one said, `` is n't something they're paying a lot of attention to, and they're not likely to until things start to go bang in the night.'' Although council states privately welcomed the foreign warships sent to the gulf last year to escort tankers, their presence remains a touchy political issue and the governments might not recognize the mine problem before anti-mine vessels leave the gulf, one Western source said. There now are at least 16 foreign mine sweepers in the gulf region, including six <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION>, three British, two Italian, two French, one Belgian, one Dutch and one or more Soviet. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officers say there are no plans for the 30-year-old, wooden-hulled American craft to leave and suggest some might remain indefinitely.
</TEXT>
