<HEAD>Court Considers Whether All-White Jury Was Unfair to Black
Defendant</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID FOX</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is deciding whether excluding prospective jurors because of race violates a criminal defendant's right to a jury representing a cross-section of the community. The high court ruled in 1986 that racially motivated disqualifications violate equal-protection provisions of the law. However, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> attorney <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Unsinn </PERSON> asked the justices Tuesday to expand on that decision by ordering a new trial for <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Teague </PERSON>, a black man convicted of armed robbery and attempted murder. An all-white jury found <PERSON> Teague </PERSON> guilty in August 1978 after a <LOCATION> Cook </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> prosecutor used all of his peremptory challenges _ the disqualification of potential jurors without stating a reason _ to exclude 10 blacks from the jury. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled on April 30, 1986, in a case called <PERSON> Batson </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Kentucky </ORGANIZATION>, that a defendant's right to equal protection would be violated if prosecutors disqualified potential jurors based on their race. It later held that the ruling does not apply to convicted criminals who had exhausted direct appeals in state courts prior to the announcement of the <PERSON> Batson </PERSON> decision. While the <PERSON> Batson </PERSON> ruling came too late to help <PERSON> Teague </PERSON>, his attorney argued that the exclusion of blacks also violated her client's Sixth Amendment right to a jury representing a cross-section of the community. `` Because the prosecutor took affirmative action to destroy the representative makeup of that jury, we did not get the protection that the Sixth Amendment guarantees,'' <PERSON> Unsinn </PERSON> said. Assistant Illinois Attorney General <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bindi </PERSON> argued that it is impossible to ensure a representative cross-section of the community for every trial and said the fact that <PERSON> Teague </PERSON>'s jury was all white did not necessarily deny him a fair trial. `` Cross-sectionalism is not the litmus test of impartiality,'' <PERSON> Bindi </PERSON> said. `` To equate jury impartiality with some form of mix on the jury ... is to take a dangerous step toward saying that juries be filled by quotas.'' The 7th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in May 1987 that past <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decisions make clear the fair cross-section requirement of the Sixth Amendment does not apply to the jury itself, but only to the pool of potential jurors from which the jury is chosen. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> is expected to rule on the case sometime next year.
</TEXT>
