<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GEORGETOWN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> used 3,000 $ 1 bills to pay the county taxes on his tool-rental business, he thought his feelings were clear and the matter was closed. But Clear Creek County Treasurer <PERSON> Geraldine </PERSON> <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> may have upstaged <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>. She returned his change of $ 110 mostly in nickels, dimes and pennies. `` I guess he was just trying to make a statement,'' said <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>. `` I just gave him all the change I could dish out. I mean, turnabout is fair play.'' <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> said he enjoyed <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON>'s response to his `` silent protest.'' He said he was trying to make a point when he paid his $ 2,890 in taxes in person with an old gunpowder crate full of $ 1 bills. `` I do n't mind paying my property taxes,'' said <PERSON> Walters </PERSON>. `` But sometimes they -LRB- county officials -RRB- have a tendency not to realize how much money they're taking from people. `` I only get to see $ 3,000 twice a year _ once when I borrow it to pay my income taxes and once when I borrow to pay my property taxes.'' <PERSON> Thompson </PERSON> said she has known <PERSON> Walters </PERSON> for about seven years and realized he has an `` ornery'' sense of humor. She said it could have been worse: `` He could have undone the bundles and just thrown them at me.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 At first, teacher <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> was n't sure what her third grade students at <ORGANIZATION> Greenville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Elementary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> could learn from a truckload of pumpkins But her experiment turned out to be a lesson in entrepreneurship for the youngsters. Ms. <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> lent her class $ 100 to start their own business, called the Pumpkin Patch. She then persuaded her brother-in-law, orchard owner <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Huber </PERSON>, to give the class more than 300 pumpkins. Ms. <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON>'s loan covered the cost of paint and brushes, which the children use to draw goblin faces on the pumpkins. The youngsters then sold their handiwork back to <PERSON> Huber </PERSON> at $ 1.50 each. He, in turn, sells them to the public. The students already have made enough to pay off their loan. Ms. <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> expects the class to turn a profit of about $ 500, which will be used to pay for several field trips. Extra money will be given to the school to purchase playground equipment, she said. `` At the beginning of the year, many of these kids had a difficult time calculating the value of money and being able to make the right change, but this project has really gotten through to them,'' Ms. <PERSON> Cooley </PERSON> said.
