<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-NCAA     10-05 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-NCAA,490</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Studies NCAA's Disciplinary Practices</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Prenoon EDT top planned.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Basketball coach <PERSON> Jerry </PERSON> <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>'s long feud with the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> is being refereed by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in a case testing the collegiate organization's disciplinary authority. The court's decision could affect, among other things, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Collegiate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>'s investigations into alleged drug use by some athletes. The justices, who granted an <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> appeal last February, were to hear arguments in the case today. A decision is expected by July. <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>, head coach at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> since 1973, is trying to preserve the victory he won in lower courts and avoid a two-year suspension for alleged <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> violations. Following a 30-month investigation, <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> officials said <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON> arranged for a student to get a `` B'' grade without attending class, provided free air fare to a student-athlete, encouraged individuals to give the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> false information to impede its probe, falsely certified <ORGANIZATION> UNLV </ORGANIZATION>'s program as complying with <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> rules and failed to comport with high ethical standards. The <ORGANIZATION> Nevada </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruled that <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON> was denied due-process during the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> investigation that led to his suspension. But to reach that conclusion, the state court had to find that the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION>, a private organization, acted with governmental power. The justices' handling of that larger issue will affect coaches and athletes at state-run <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> member schools across the nation. Individuals and private organizations generally can not violate someone's constitutional rights. Only a government and its agents can do that because the Constitution protects against governmental _ not private _ wrongdoing. Courts call the concept the `` doctrine of state action.'' The <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> is a private organization representing nearly 1,000 colleges and universities. But in the <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON> case, the state court said the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> was acting as a surrogate for <ORGANIZATION> UNLV </ORGANIZATION>, a state university. `` The right to discipline public employees is traditionally the exclusive prerogative of the state,'' the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> court said. `` <ORGANIZATION> UNLV </ORGANIZATION> can not escape responsibility for disciplinary action against employees by delegating that duty to a private entity.'' Because the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> investigators were acting as agents of a state school, the state court ruled, <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON> was entitled to more due process _ more opportunities to be heard and more information about the investigation. The <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION>, insisting its investigation was not `` state action,'' sought help from the nation's highest court. If the justices agree with the <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> court, the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> will find itself in a curious position. It will have to afford more due-process rights to coaches and athletes at state-run schools than those who work for or attend private schools. The <ORGANIZATION> UNLV </ORGANIZATION> program was placed on two years' probation in 1977 for recruiting violations, and the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> that same year ordered the school to suspend <PERSON> Tarkanian </PERSON>. His court fight staved off the suspension, and won him the right to have the <ORGANIZATION> NCAA </ORGANIZATION> pay some of his legal fees.
