<FIRST>r w PM-Scotus-Set-Aside     10-05 0632</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Scotus-Set-Aside,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Hears Case On Minority Role In Public Works Projects</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top planned after conclusion of arguments, scheduled for noon
EDT</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The power of states and local governments to require minority participation in public works projects is being explored by the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in a key affirmative action dispute. The justices were to hear arguments today over a <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, program that set aside 30 percent of the value of all municipal building projects for minority participation. The court is expected to decide by July whether the plan should be reinstated. The plan was challenged successfully in a lower court by J.A. <ORGANIZATION> Croson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, a building contractor. At stake could be similar set-aside plans established by most states and some 190 local governments. The case also is attracting widespread attention because of what it might foretell about the court's future approach to other forms of affirmative action and alleged reverse discrimination. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> is participating in his first case involving preferential treatment for minorities since joining the court last February. He replaced Justice <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, who often cast the deciding vote on affirmative action issues in the closely divided court. Set-aside programs also have caused some deep divisions and seemingly contradictory views within the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, for example, said in 1984 he favored channeling billions of additional contract dollars to minority-owned firms. And the administration generally has looked upon public works set-asides more sympathetically than other affirmative action quotas it sternly opposes. But the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, responding to an invitation from the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in a case similar to the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> dispute, challenged the constitutionality of set-asides. The <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> plan was declared unlawful in September 1987 by the 4th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>. The appeals court said there is insufficient evidence that <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> city officials discriminated against minority-owned businesses in the past. Also, the appeals court said the city's 30 percent quota appeared to be a completely arbitrary figure that `` simply emerged from the mists.'' <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> adopted the plan in 1983 to require that a prime contractor on any city building project subcontract at least 30 percent of the value of the project to firms that are at least one-half minority owned. The minorities named in the plan are blacks, Hispanics, Orientals, Indians, Eskimos and Aleuts. The 4th Circuit court, in invalidating the program, relied heavily on a 1986 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that struck down an affirmative action plan in <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION> designed to protect from lay-offs the jobs of minority teachers with less seniority than whites. The justices in that case said preferential treatment of minorities must be narrowly tailored to avoid hurting whites. The justices also restricted the power of employers to adopt affirmative action programs when there has not been proof the employers practiced past discrimination. But civil rights groups point to a 1980 <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> ruling that allows <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to earmark 10 percent of federal public works contracts for minority-controlled businesses. The court also has upheld other forms of affirmative action programs in a string of recent decisions. Minorities make up about half of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>'s population, and minority-owned businesses received less than 1 percent of the value of city contracts prior to adoption of the set-aside. The plan was challenged by J.A. <ORGANIZATION> Croson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> after its bid _ the only one submitted to install stainless steel urinals and water closets at the city jail was rejected. City officials refused to award the contract even though <PERSON> Croson </PERSON> said there was only one minority contractor that could help on that project and <PERSON> Croson </PERSON> considered that company unqualified. <PERSON> Croson </PERSON> also said the cost of the project would rise by $ 7,663 if the minority contractor took part. The city then called for new bids.
