<DATELINE>SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Campaign strategists for <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> say they are trying to win the nation's most populous state by pursuing not only the `` Reagan Democrats'' but also more moderate Democrats who might be attracted to a `` future-oriented'' <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> candidate distinct from President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. `` A number of swing voters are not <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> <PERSON> Democrats </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Merksamer </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> state campaign chairman, said in reference to those Democrats who voted for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in the past two elections. `` They are more moderate Democrats,'' who are `` not necessarily in sinc'' with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s conservative ideas. With a Democratic edge in the state's voter registration, the Republicans must attract Democrats _ as they have in past elections _ to win the state with the most electoral votes _ 47. Public opinion polls show the race virtually even, making <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> a critical toss-up state. Its diverse economy and broad demographic and social makeup makes <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> an expensive state in which to campaign, but both candidates are making an all-out push. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign will devote most of its resources in the coming weeks to winning swing voters and <PERSON> Democrats </PERSON>, said senior campaign consultant <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON>, who is heading the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> effort. He said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> forces are confident they have already shored up their Republican support in the tight contest. In comments to reporters traveling with the campaign Tuesday, <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Merksamer </PERSON> refused to disclose projected budget figures for the <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> effort. The moderate Democrats, many of whom live in the <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION> area, do not respond `` with the same emotional intensity'' to the so-called value issues that are popular with the Democrats who crossed party lines to give President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> his two general election victories, said <PERSON> Merksamer </PERSON>. The campaign believes they are more likely to be swayed by speeches like the one <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made here Tuesday in which he proposed a program to promote volunteer service by young people, he said. The proposal was aimed at showing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to be a strong leader with `` future-oriented'' ideas, <PERSON> Lacy </PERSON> said. A TV ad attacking Democratic presidential nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> for the pollution in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> under his governorship has played well in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, but the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign does not see environmental concerns as decisive in the election, said <PERSON> Merksamer </PERSON>. He said it is primarily a coastal population that sees the environment as a top issue, while voters inland are more concerned about crime, taxes, and defense both from a foreign policy perspective and an economic one since much of <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s economy is driven by defense contracting. Besides the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> commercial, the campaign has been running a `` crime quiz'' commercial attacking <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, and positive ads featuring excerpts from <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s lively speech at the Republican National Convention in August, and another `` feel-good'' ad narrated by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s wife <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON>.
