<HEAD>Honduras Wants United Nations To Evict Nicaraguan Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> is calling for the creation of a <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> peace force to evacuate thousands of Nicaraguan rebels based in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and relocate them far from its borders. The Honduran proposal, unveiled Tuesday night by Foreign Minister <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON>, also would apply to the comparatively small number of leftist rebels from <ORGANIZATION> El </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Salvador </ORGANIZATION> who operate out of <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Redman </PERSON> said Tuesday night he had not seen <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON>' speech and had no comment. Nonetheless, the speech appeared to signal <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>' determination to end the tacit cooperation it has been providing to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by allowing the anti-communist rebels to use <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> as a staging area for attacks against <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> Underscoring <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON>' apparent effort to disassociate <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy was his description of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, along with the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, as a `` hegemonistic power.'' <PERSON> Lopez </PERSON> <PERSON> Contreras </PERSON> called on <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> to oversee the creation of a peace force comprised of troops from <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>. The force would guarantee the `` non-use'' of Honduran territory by foreign insurgents, he said, adding that the proposed unit should be authorized to use force, if necessary, to achieve its objectives. The unit should locate the combatants in Nicaraguan and <LOCATION> Salvadoran </LOCATION> territories, `` far away from Honduran borders,'' he said. `` Their relocation in third countries should be carried out from sites in <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. whose governments have declared themselves neutral,'' he added. The proposal represents a revised and updated version of a plan which the Hondurans set forth in November 1987. At the time, however, there were relatively few Contras in the border era. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, as a front-line state which shares a long border with <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>, has been a major pillar of American policy toward <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> for more than six years. As a deterrent to potential Nicaraguan aggression, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> maintains about 1,200 troops in the country and has carried out numerous <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military training missions there. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> also has been a major recipient of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> economic aid. But <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> always has been uneasy about the presence of the U.S.-backed Contras along the border, fearing that the situation could be used by the militarily powerful Sandinista government as an excuse to invade <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>. There have been numerous cross-border incidents involving the two countries. The situation in the region has changed radically since February, when the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> rejected an administration proposal for additional military aid to the Contras. Thousands of Contras have fled across the border to the <LOCATION> Honduran </LOCATION> base camps where <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> foreign aid officials have been carrying out a large scale humanitarian assistance program. Under an agreement the Contras signed with the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> in March, the aid was to have been distributed to Contras in several designated zones inside <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>. But that plan was never implemented, leaving many Contras no choice but to go to the border area for sustenance. <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> has watched these developments unfold with a deep sense of unease, worried about the possibility that the Contras may settle in the border area for an indefinite period. The rebels and the <LOCATION> Sadinista </LOCATION> government signed a temporary cease-fire agreement on March 23 but have been unable to agree on a lasting peace accord.
