<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Republican <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, with two mock debates and dozens of issues briefings behind him, says he'll `` just be myself'' when he faces Democrat <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> in tonight's nationally broadcast confrontation between the vice presidential candidates With <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s media guru, <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailes </PERSON>, and a host of top campaign strategists at his side, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION> Tuesday night. He declined to tip his hand about debate strategy, saying only, `` tune in and find out.'' But it's no secret that <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> will be on the attack against Democratic presidential candidate <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, not the <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> senator, whom the Republicans portray as closer to them on the issues than to the Democrats. `` <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is running for president, and he's the one I'm very concerned about becoming president. It would be a very troubling notion for many Americans,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> told reporters on his campaign plane en route to <LOCATION> Omaha </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> plans a brief walk-through today of the <ORGANIZATION> Omaha </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auditorium </ORGANIZATION>, scene of the debate. He sounded upbeat and appeared confident Tuesday as he chatted with reporters in the first such on-the-record session he's had on his plane. `` I'm going to just be myself,'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said. `` I will be prepared to answer any and all questions.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> said he sees the debate as `` an opportunity to communicate with the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> public in an unedited version.'' `` They'll be able to see <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> as I really am,'' he said. `` The <LOCATION> Americ