<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> returned home to catch up on gubernatorial duties after courting crucial voters in the industrial <LOCATION> Midwest </LOCATION> with a promise of a White House that cares about the plight of struggling families. `` I care about working people and working families and that's the difference between <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democrats and Republicans,'' the Democratic presidential nominee told a rally Tuesday afternoon in <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> `` We care.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was in <LOCATION> Toledo </LOCATION> to tour its Jeep assembly plant, where he received a warm welcome from its union workers. Earlier he addressed students and faculty at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, and he ended his campaign day by attending two private receptions in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> D.C. </LOCATION>, with <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> luminaries. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was spending most of today at the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statehouse </ORGANIZATION> and was scheduled to meet with reporters this afternoon. He also was attending a rally with supporters after tonight's vice presidential debate between Democrat <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> and Republican <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. Because of the focus on the space shuttle mission and the vice presidential debate, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> offered no new proposals this week but sought to bring together his initiatives under the umbrella issue of restoring <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dominance in the world marketplace. He also underscored the theme of his campaign's largest advertising effort _ a four-ad series portraying <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as a product of media handlers who has presented no viable solutions to the nation's problems. `` He offers slogans and symbols; we offer solutions,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` This nation did n't become the greatest on earth because we were satisfied with the status quo.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also repeatedly likened this year's race to the <ORGANIZATION> Kennedy-Nixon </ORGANIZATION> contest of 1960, at one point comparing <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s tactics to those of <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> in the race 28 years ago `` They said the same thing about <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> in 1960 _ all that gloom and doom,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` And what was he saying? ` We can do better.''' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> aides, while conceding they still trail <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, have said privately in the past two days that some of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s support appears to be waning and that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> hopes to attract the growing number of undecided voters in the campaign's final five weeks. `` The stakes are very high and the race is geting even closer,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told his <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> audience. In the <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> speech, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> delivered a sharply worded attack on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and said his rival was running from `` a record of failure and walking away from every major challenge he has faced.'' He told the college audience that he and <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> would restore <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s leadership in the world economy through innovative business and labor partnerships at home and a tough trade stance abroad. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was trying to pin the `` gloom and doom'' label on Democrats because he had no answers to the trade and budget deficits and the decline of research and development in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. `` Cite these facts and <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will tell you that you're downgrading <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the same thing <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Nixon </PERSON> did in 1960 when <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> was telling us to look to a new frontier,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said `` My friends, if we disregard these facts we endanger <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' He also boasted: `` I'm running for president on my record. Mr. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is running away from his _ a record of failure and walking away from every major challenge he has faced.'' There were no new proposals in the speech. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> repeated his familiar call for business-labor partnerships, tough enforcement of the new trade law, reduction of the trade and budget deficits and `` some reasonable limits on the merger and acquisition binge that continues to sweep this country.''
