<HEAD>Dukakis Appeals Federal Control Over Guard Units</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTOPHER B. DALY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is fighting in court for the rights of governors to veto federally issued training assignments for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, a position that a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> attorney said was a `` dagger aimed at the heart of national defense.'' In a hearing Tuesday in federal appeals court, <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> Attorney General <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilkins </PERSON> argued that governors have a right under the `` militia clause'' of the Constitution to veto National Guard training assignments. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s civil division, said `` this is a political case'' and warned that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, might regret a victory if elected president. `` The view from <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> is very different from the view from <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> said. If each of the 50 governors were allowed to opt out of controversial training assignments, he said, `` you end up with potential chaos.'' <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> said the state's position amounted to `` a dagger aimed at the heart of national defense.'' The issue began when federal authorities ordered 13 public relations specialists from the <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> to train in <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> in May and June. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> withheld his consent and filed suit on Jan. 29 seeking to block the mission. However, the court upheld the authority of federal officials on May 6 on the grounds that <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> troops are sworn to federal duty as well as state duty. The mission was carried out. The three-judge panel of the 1st U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> said it would review the arguments. Lawyers said it could take months to issue a ruling. Afterward, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' Statehouse press secretary, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was trying to uphold a principle endorsed by many governors of both parties. `` There is a very important principle at stake here _ a 200-year tradition of the states being responsible for the training of the militia,'' <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> said. Asked if the <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> campaign was concerned that the governor's position could be used against him in the presidential campaign to portray <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> as `` soft'' on defense, <PERSON> Dorsey </PERSON> shot back: `` Who's going to make that argument, <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> He was referring to Republican vice presidential nominee <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, who came under criticism for seeking a position in the <ORGANIZATION> Indiana </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> during the Vietnam War, a status that spared him from combat duty. <PERSON> Bolton </PERSON> warned that if <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> prevailed, it would `` permit governors to interfere in sensitive foreign policy decisions.'' Specifically, he said, the Constitution gave <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> the power to enact the 1986 Montgomery Amendment, which prohibited governors from objecting to <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> assignments in peacetime unless their states were facing an emergency such as a flood. The <LOCATION> Massac