<HEAD>State Governments Healthy Now, Vulnerable to Future Problems</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 State governments are vulnerable to new financial strains in 1989, despite their success this year in maintaining services without major tax increases, according to a study by the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Governors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>. In its biannual survey, the governors said a drop next year in federal aid could trigger economic problems for states, since their budget surpluses are narrowing. `` These balances, if they hold as projected, are already at their lowest point in the 12 years we have been producing the survey,'' said <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Scheppach </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> NGA </ORGANIZATION>'s executive director. The survey released Tuesday showed revenue collections exceeded expenditures in all three fiscal years studied. But the states are reporting steady growth in spending: up 6.3 percent in fiscal 1987, 6 percent the following year and an estimated 6.8 percent in fiscal 1989. In the 1988 legislative session, 27 states passed tax laws, but most involved minor changes to conform with the new federal tax structure. The new tax laws were expected to yield less than an additional $ 1 billion, with most of the money generated by motor vehicle fuel tax increases. In general, state economies seem to be growing. While the <LOCATION> Northeast </LOCATION> and Far West continue to enjoy solid growth, most states elsewhere that were hurt by poor farm performances and a downturn in energy prices seem to be making significant economic and budgetary improvements. Here is an overview of the regions: _ <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>: The region enjoys the lowest unemployment rate and highest personal income growth in the country The positive economic signs are manifested in the highest percentage increase in state expenditures projected for fiscal 1989. _ <LOCATION> Mideast </LOCATION>: Unemployment rates are lower than the national average and increases in personal income are 1 percent higher than the national average General fund expenditures are slightly higher than the aggregate figure for all states. _ Great Lakes: The region's unemployment rate is higher than the national average In addition, the expected fiscal 1989 expenditures show the lowest growth rate in the country. _ The Plains: These states have made a recovery from the economic and budgetary doldrums of a few years ago Since the March governors' association survey, the unemployment rate dropped dramatically from 5.5 percent to 4.2 percent. But the annual growth in personal income also declined in the same period. The growth in expenditures is slightly above the national average, with the exception of <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION>. _ Southeast: Unemployment has declined and personal income has risen since the March survey But the fiscally troubled states of <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> make an analysis of the region's economy difficult. _ Southwest: This region has the highest unemployment rate and the second lowest percentage increase in personal income, in part because of the oil bust in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, the state that dominates the area _ <LOCATION> Rocky </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountain </LOCATION> states: This area struggles to improve its economic and fiscal health Personal income growth is the lowest in the nation, while unemployment is slightly above the national average. _ Far West: Growth here continues strong, with personal income increasing at an average of 6.7 percent annually, led by <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> with a rise of 8.9 percent and <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> at 7.2 percent Unemployment is very close to the national average.
