<HEAD>With PM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to tone down his attacks on Democratic presidential rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, a top aide contends, but <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> continues to sprinkle speeches with a hefty dose of opponent bashing. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of staff, <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, told reporters on Tuesday that the Republican presidential candidate wanted to get away from the appearance of waging a negative rather than issue-oriented campaign. `` He was uncomfortable with a perception forming that his is a campaign that was not talking about issues as much, because he has been talking about issues,'' said <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>. He cited <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s first campaign stop Tuesday as evidence of the new approach. In a speech to the business-oriented <ORGANIZATION> Comstock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> made barely a passing reference to <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. He proposed a $ 100 million program to encourage community volunteer service by young people. A new foundation, chaired by the president, would work with existing volunteer programs and act as a clearinghouse to help get more youths involved in community service. Today's campaigning in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> included remarks on a companion topic _ what society can do for children and education. But after Tuesday's speech calling for a Youth Engaged in Service to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> program of voluntary charitable activity, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> went back to some familiar <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> one-liners. The barbs he delivered in his stump speech to a rowdy rally on the steps of the <LOCATION> Riverside </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> courthouse lacked a bit of the sting that has characterized similar recent speeches. But he unveiled a new one-liner commenting on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>' proposal to reduce the deficit by beefing up <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> collection of unpaid taxes. `` Politicians used to promise a chicken in every pot,'' he said. `` He promises a tax agent in every kitchen.'' By the time he got to a late-afternoon rally in <LOCATION> Albuquerque </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was revved up for attack. Referring derisively to his opponent as `` the liberal governor of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` I love calling him that. I love it.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` does n't even dare use the big ` L' word'' anymore. He trotted out his environmental attack on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, ridiculing the Democrat for making an environmental pitch in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> when he was the governor `` who wanted to dump the crud from <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>'' in a waste site offshore from <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Jersey </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> laced the negative comments into a speech in which he portrayed himself as an environmentalist, `` in the mold of <LOCATION> Teddy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Roosevelt </LOCATION>,'' and a man concerned about education and crime and one who wants to build a more caring nation. He noted <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> had proclaimed himself tough on crime. `` If you believe that, he's got some bottled water from the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harbor </LOCATION> to sell you,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in one of his favorite references to the severe pollution in the governor's homestate harbor. But <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> maintained this week's agenda would be devoted to more positive issue-based speeches. `` He would like his campaign to talk about issues ... and not be caught up in an attack on his opponent,'' he said. That does not mean that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is going soft on <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, said <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>, forecasting `` future speeches that draw sharp contrasts between the two candidates.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> today was visiting <ORGANIZATION> Arapahoe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> where the intinerary included a tour of the science lab and remarks at an assembly where National Merit Scholarship finalists will be recognized. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> then was holding a rally at the 16th Street Mall before heading off for a campaign stop in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.
