<HEAD>Reagan Authorized Free Hand for CIA on Counterrorism</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed intelligence authorizations in 1984 and 1985 giving <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> agents broad anti-terrorism powers that some administration officials saw as `` a license to kill,'' according to a published report. The authorizations `` deemed'' as lawful any covert actions _ including potentially violent ones _ taken in `` good faith'' by <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence agents against terrorists, according to a report in Wednesday's editions of The Washington Post. The language of the findings seemingly was ambiguous, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. Actions taken in good faith and as part of an approved operation would be deemed lawful in advance, but also they `` must be'' lawful, sources told the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION>. The newspaper quoted a former <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> official, whom it did not identify, as saying the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> orders were a `` go-anywhere, do-anything'' authority. The language of the findings caused disputes among administration officials, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said, because actions that could be authorized under the findings might conflict with earlier presidential executive orders banning any direct or indirect involvement of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence agents in assassinations. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> quoted a source as saying the language was specifically designed to `` circumvent the assassination ban'' and protect <ORGANIZATION> CIA </ORGANIZATION> agents who might take part in foreign strike teams. White House spokesman <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Hall </PERSON> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> he knew nothing about the findings late Tuesday night. The <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported that unidentified White House officials said Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would have been given a copy of or would have had access to the findings. A <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> spokesman and <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON>, who was White House chief of staff at the time <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed the 1984 finding, had no comment, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> signed the first finding on Nov. 13, 1984, shortly after his landslide reelection victory, the report said, because <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials had become frustrated with car-bombings at <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> facilities and the taking of American hostages. Congressional intelligence committees were not informed of the crucial language in the findings, the report said. The authorization was rescinded on April 10, 1985, a month after a car bomb exploded, killing 80 people in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> near the residence of a leader of one faction of Iranian fundamentalists. The second authorization which included similar language was signed by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> on Aug. 11, 1985, two months after the highjacking of <ORGANIZATION> TWA </ORGANIZATION> Flight 847 in which <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> diver <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Steedham </PERSON> was killed. The intelligence panels were briefed after the signing of the second finding, the <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> said.
