<HEAD>President Says Government Abandoning Peace Proposal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM WELLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Virgilio </PERSON> <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> withdrew a peace proposal to leftist guerrillas because of a wave of rebel attacks, and the army has been ordered to attack the insurgents, a cabinet minister said. `` It is incomprehensible that the answer by subversive groups to a generous peace proposal would be so violent and criminal,'' the minister of government, <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Gaviria </PERSON> <PERSON> Trujillo </PERSON>, said in a broadcast interview Tuesday. <PERSON> Trujillo </PERSON> is in charge of internal security in <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>. Last month the president offered a cease-fire, negotiations, pardons to guerrillas who surrendered and a chance for rebel leaders to speak before congress. All six of <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>'s leftist guerrilla groups rejected the plan, calling it an ultimatum for surrender. <PERSON> Gaviria </PERSON> was particularly critical of the country's largest guerrilla group, the <ORGANIZATION> Colombian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revolutionary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION>, known by its Spanish acronym as the <ORGANIZATION> FARC </ORGANIZATION>. Sunday and Monday <ORGANIZATION> FARC </ORGANIZATION> attacks killed 12 soldiers, six policemen and three civilians, the <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> said Monday. `` The government authorizes full institutional support for the armed forces to confront the guerrillas, because weakness or complacency does n't result in peace,'' <PERSON> Gaviria </PERSON> said in an interview with the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> radio station <ORGANIZATION> Caracol </ORGANIZATION>. Minister of Justice <PERSON> Guillermo </PERSON> <PERSON> Plazas </PERSON> said the guerrillas' answer to `` the olive branch offered by President <PERSON> Barco </PERSON> has been attacks on the army, blowing up of pipelines and setting off bombs.'' The <ORGANIZATION> FARC </ORGANIZATION> has used a cease-fire during the last four years `` to cheat the government'' by building up its strength, Plazas said in a broadcast interview with the <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> radio station <ORGANIZATION> RCN </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> FARC </ORGANIZATION> signed a truce with the government of President <PERSON> Belisario </PERSON> <PERSON> Betancur </PERSON> four years ago. There has been sporadic fighting between the <ORGANIZATION> FARC </ORGANIZATION> and government security forces during the truce. Another guerrilla group, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, has blown up the country's main oil pipeline 85 times in the last two years. Last Saturday the guerrilla group blew up the pipeline, which carries 225,000 barrels of oil a day from the <ORGANIZATION> Canon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Limon </ORGANIZATION> field in the northeast state of <LOCATION> Arauca </LOCATION>. Last Wednesday the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> set off a bomb in <LOCATION> Bogota </LOCATION> as the car of a <ORGANIZATION> Texaco </ORGANIZATION> executive was passing by. The executive, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Buttle </PERSON>, a Canadian, was not injured. And last July the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> kidnapped the owner of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, of <LOCATION> Houston </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Jake </PERSON> <PERSON> Gambini </PERSON>. There has been no word on <PERSON> Gambini </PERSON>'s fate.
