<FIRST>r w PM-AIDS-Pregnancy     10-05 0733</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AIDS-Pregnancy,720</SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers Hope To Use AZT in Pregnant Women Infected With AIDS</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Pregnant women infected with the deadly AIDS virus would be treated with the drug AZT in an attempt to protect their unborn children if an experiment being planned by researchers gets the go-ahead from review boards. `` The reason we think -LRB- prevention of infection of the fetus -RRB- might be possible is that AZT prevents the replication of the virus,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Hoth </PERSON>, director of the AIDS program at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Allergy </ORGANIZATION> and Infectious Diseases. `` It's theoretically possible that the AZT, if it reaches the fetus, might prevent it from establishing an infection,'' he said, referring to the drug formally known as azidothymidine. <PERSON> Hoth </PERSON> said in a telephone interview Tuesday night that the studies are still at least several months away, as a formal proposal has not yet been completed, and the proposal would have to pass numerous hurdles in the form of review boards concerned with the safety of such tests. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Randall </PERSON>, the institute's spokeswoman, went even further, saying the likelihood of an early start to such a study is `` still pretty tenuous.'' `` There's a lot of steps between now and the beginning of a study with pregnant women,'' she said. As of Sept. 26, AIDS had been diagnosed in 74,447 Americans, of whom 1,185 were children under age 13, and 924 of those children were infected at birth, according to the federal <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION>. Of the 41,925 deaths among AIDS patients, 672 have been children, the <ORGANIZATION> CDC </ORGANIZATION> reported. `` Most new infections of children with AIDS are related to an infected mother,'' <PERSON> Hoth </PERSON> said. Among the still unanswered questions are exactly how the child gets infected, he said. `` The virus might be transmitted in utero, that is, across the placenta,'' <PERSON> Hoth </PERSON> said. `` The second possibility is it might be transmitted at the time of childbirth through some blood-borne transmission. The third possibility is that the child becomes infected through close association with the mother after birth, such as through breast-feeding, although that remains totally speculative, totally unproven.'' However, he said, `` It's the widespread opinion of most experts in the field that one of the most important ways to stop the infection in children is to prevent the infection by catching it as early as possible. That leads you to the necessity of treating the infected mother.'' The proposal will call for studies on only a few dozen women who would be in their third trimester of pregnancy to limit the possibility of birth defects, he said. `` These are mothers that may be infected with the virus, but may not have symptoms of AIDS,'' he said. Animal model studies using mice have shown that AZT _ the only drug approved by the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> for AIDS patients _ prevents the transmission of viral infection from an infected mother to the offspring, he said, adding that he believed there were no birth defects in those studies. However, he noted that those tests did not involve the human immunodeficiency virus, or HIV, that causes AIDS, but a closely related retrovirus. The side-effects of AZT encountered by some people taking the drug include a decrease in production of red or white blood cells, and such problems are a major concern for the researchers, he said. `` That's the whole question here,'' <PERSON> Hoth </PERSON> said. `` Will it be safe? What is the risk-benefit ratio? So we're proceeding cautiously. There will be consultation with many experts. We have obstetricians on our team, pediatricians. We'll be talking with other experts, including ethicists, on this issue.'' The institutional review boards that would have to approve the studies once the protocol is completed `` are charged with the protection of human subjects in clinical trials, so they must review the protocol with an eye toward the risk-benefit for both the mother and the child,'' <PERSON> Hoth </PERSON> said. `` Before we send it for review, we want to have consensus among all of the experts.'' AIDS, or acquired immune deficiency syndrome, is a contagious disease that attacks the body's immune system, rendering it incapable of resisting other diseases and infections. The virus most often is spread through close contact with blood, blood products or semen from infected persons. No one is known to have recovered from AIDS, whose chief victims have been homosexual men and intravenous drug users.
</TEXT>
