<HEAD>Broader Protection For Whistleblowers Okayed By House</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The House has approved and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> a bill strengthening protection for whistelblowers who expose federal waste and mismanagement. The measure was approved Tuesday on a 418-0 vote. Sponsors said the bill was needed because the Office of Special Counsel, established to represent the interests of whistleblowers, was not doing its job. The bill is designed to reverse decisions of courts and the <ORGANIZATION> Merit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> _ a federal judicial agency _ that made it difficult for whistleblowers to win their cases. The legislation would define clearly the Office of Special Counsel's role as one of protecting whistleblowers. In some cases, the counsel has proceeded against whistleblowers who came to the office for help. The measure would make the Office of Special Counsel an independent agency. It currently is part of the <ORGANIZATION> Merit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> _ a quasi-judicial body that hears employees' appeals The bill also would: _ Alter the burden of proof in reprisal cases against whistleblowers The employee would have to show only that the agency's knowledge of the whistleblowing was a factor in his or her punishment, rather than a `` significant'' or `` dominant'' factor as required under current law. _ Require an agency to demonstrate `` with clear and convincing evidence'' that whistleblowing was not a material factor in the personnel action Currently the courts require a `` preponderance of evidence,'' an easier standard for government agencies. _ Expand the definition of prohibited personnel practices to include reprisals against workers who cooperate with inspectors general or the special counsel, those who testify in government proceedings, and those who refuse to obey an order that violates the law _ Allow individuals facing reprisals to appeal their cases directly to the merit board
