<HEAD>Brazil To Enact New Constitution, Consolidate Democracy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> today is to enact a new constitution consolidating the country's return to democratic government after 21 years of right-wing military rule. `` This is a historic date for our country,'' President <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> told Brazilians Tuesday night in a nationwide TV broadcast. `` We have reached the end of a long path ... My mission of helping the country through its transition to democracy is fulfilled.'' The 559 legislators doubling as a constituent assembly worked for 19 months on the 245-article document that governs everything from interest rates to mining rights and land reform. The charter is <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s eighth since independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1822 and replaces the authoritarian document handed down by military generals in 1969. `` The new constitution will consolidate a representative and participatory democracy,'' the president of the constituent assembly, Rep. <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON> <PERSON> Guimaraes </PERSON> said in a press conference. `` For the first time the individual will have precedence over the state.'' <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>, who at times fought bitterly against left-leaning measures in the new document, said in his broadcast he would be the constitution's `` greatest servant.'' In earlier broadcasts, <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> made veiled threats that if certain articles were passed, the military might refuse to respect the new constitution. The constitution removes many of the arbitrary powers used by the military government during its harsh rule. The document abolishes the president's power to simply decree laws, ends censorship, prohibits torture, guarantees political rights and broadens workers' right to strike and to unionize. Nationalistic legislators also managed to limit mineral mining to national companies and prohibit further oil drilling risk contracts between the state-run <ORGANIZATION> Petrobras </ORGANIZATION>, which has a monopoly on oil exploration and drilling in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, and international companies. At the same time, the right-wing scored a victory, managing to water-down a land reform law that protects `` productive land'' from expropriation. The law further stalls <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON>'s program to distribute land to 1.4 million peasant families, in a country where 2 percent of landowners hold 60 pecent of arable land. Judiciary analysts have said, however, there are many articles in the hefty document that will be difficult to define or to enforce in complimentary legislation. <ORGANIZATION> Guimaraes </ORGANIZATION>, 72, said the charter would be respected by all _ including the Armed Forces. `` The military period left deep marks. There is an awareness that the regime is good and from the <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forces </ORGANIZATION> we have heard only words of support and confidence in the stability of democracy,'' <ORGANIZATION> Guimaraes </ORGANIZATION> said. The enactment of the new constituion will be marked by day-long celebrations starting early today with an open-air mass before the twin-domed <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and a reception for delegates from more than 30 Latin American and Portuguese-speaking nations. <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> 58, became president in 1985 after President-elect <PERSON> Tancredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Neves </PERSON> died before taking office.
