games are 1992, sted 1994.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> plans to do some research to find out why its coverage of the Summer Olympics fell more than 3 rating points short of the guarantee to advertisers _ a discrepancy that could cost the network millions. <PERSON> Gerald </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> vice president for research projects, said the network probably would n't make the results of the study public, since it could bear on competition with the 1992 games. But among the likeliest contributors: the 14-hour time difference between <LOCATION> Seoul </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> that put live coverage of such popular events as gymnastics in the morning, and the late September-early-October timing. The games ended Sunday, and <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s coverage had an average <ORGANIZATION> A.C. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nielsen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> rating of 17.9 _ not counting opening and closing ceremonies _ considerably lower than the 21.2 rating <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had promised advertisers. The 1984 summer games from <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> had averaged a 23.2 for <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. Each rating point represents 904,000 households with television. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> will have to give advertisers as much as $ 70 million in commercial time, to make up for what had been promised, according to the Wall Street Journal. CBS has been awarded the TV contract for the next Winter Olympics, which will be held in 1992, and expects to make a bid for that year's summer games. The network also is studying <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s results But CBS' vice President for marketing, <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON>, thinks the 1988 Olympics suffered mainly from competition with other sports and from time pressures on viewers, especially students back in school. `` I attribute a lot of the under-delivery of ratings to the fall scheduling. It's not necessarily typical of what we can expect in future Olympics,'' said <PERSON> Poltrack </PERSON>. The 1992 games, in <LOCATION> Barcelona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, will be earlier in the summer. Nonetheless, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s six nights of Olympics coverage last week took six of the the top 10 spots in the Nielsen ratings and gave <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> a decisive victory over <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION> and CBS. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had an average 17.5 rating to <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s 12.3 and CBS' 11.2. It also provided an important promotional base for <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s new fall shows. `` The actual performance by the Olympics in key groups -LRB- of viewers -RRB- was a really dominant performance. Whether it was as dominant as anticipated, that's something else,'' said <PERSON> Jaffe </PERSON>. The closing ceremonies Sunday fell to a 12.3 rating. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> had expected closer to 20.0. CBS' `` 60 Minutes,'' `` Murder, She Wrote'' and the movie `` Cocoon'' out-rated the Sunday coverage, as did `` Liberace'' on <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>. Those four shows made up the rest of the top 10. The closing ceremonies ranked 22 out of 55 shows. During the games' first week, ratings tended to climb as the week wore on. The second week, they tended to decline. Monday's coverage was the highest-rated show of the week, with a 19.3 rating <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s `` World News Tonight'' won in the news Nielsens with a 10.0 rating. The `` CBS Evening News'' was second with a 9.8. `` NBC Nightly News,'' pre-empted on the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> by Olympics coverage, had a 9.6. The week's lowest-rated prime-time shows were: `` Live! <PERSON> Dick </PERSON> <PERSON> Clark </PERSON> Presents,'' `` Wiseguy,'' `` Mutts,'' ``