<HEAD>Bishops Object To Politician's Threats To Religious Freedom</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A high-ranking official of the ruling party has threatened to strip an outspoken Anglican bishop of his freedom to worship, but other clergmen have vowed to defy any infringement on their religious rights. <PERSON> Moses </PERSON> <PERSON> Mudavadi </PERSON>, secretary-general of the <ORGANIZATION> Kenya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION>, threatened to strip <PERSON> Biship </PERSON> <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Gitari </PERSON> of his freedom to worship after the bishop criticized the way the ruling party adopted resolutions. `` You should not be surprised if we, as a KANU government, removed that freedom from you through <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Mudavadi </PERSON> said to <PERSON> Gitari </PERSON> in comments reported Saturday by <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s three English-language newspapers. Anglican Archbishop <PERSON> Manasses </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuria </PERSON>, in a Sunday sermon to a <LOCATION> Nairobi </LOCATION> parish, said the Church of the Province of <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> would not allow anyone to deny Christians the right to worship. `` The freedom of worship is God-given and can not be taken away at will by any individual,'' <PERSON> Kuria </PERSON> said. Anglican Bishop <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Muge </PERSON>, of the <LOCATION> Rift </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Eldoret </LOCATION> province, said <PERSON> Mudavadi </PERSON>'s comments marked a `` sad moment for our independent <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>. `` Prison cells and enough graveyards must be prepared before the decree is effected because many will continue to worship whether Mr. <PERSON> Mudavadi </PERSON> likes it or not,'' <PERSON> Muge </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Muge </PERSON> and <LOCATION> Kuria </LOCATION> were quoted by the English-language <ORGANIZATION> Daily </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nation </ORGANIZATION> and The Standard. The <ORGANIZATION> Kenya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, which is owned by the ruling party, also reported <PERSON> Kuria </PERSON>'s remarks. <PERSON> Gitari </PERSON>, bishop of <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> diocese </LOCATION>, angered politicians by saying delegates to the party's conference rubber-stamped the party's resolutions. The <ORGANIZATION> Kenya </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> is <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>'s sole legal political party. On Thursday, legislators lambasted <PERSON> Gitari </PERSON>, accusing him and three other outspoken clergymen of trying to destabilize the government. It was the second time in three months parliamentarians have suspended legislative business to criticize clergy members, a sign of increasing friction between the government of President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> arap </PERSON> <PERSON> Moi </PERSON> and Anglican clergy, who have spoken out against alleged government corruption and human rights abuses. <PERSON> Muge </PERSON> said he was briefly detained on July 17 and police kept parishioners from entering his church after one run-in with the government.
