<SECOND>PM-Hollywood Teamsters, Bjt,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Threats Of Strike Violence Stop Production At Television Studio</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HORN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In two days of picketing, the <ORGANIZATION> Hollywood </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION>' strike has accomplished what scriptwriters failed to achieve over five months in their walkout: the shutdown of a studio. Citing death threats, bomb scares and sabotaged equipment, <ORGANIZATION> Cannell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it has halted production on its television shows `` Hunter'' and `` <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Spoon </PERSON>.'' It said the incidents were related to the strike by 3,200 drivers, laborers and electricians and that production would resume work only when it is safe. In a separate incident, one picket was arrested for battery Tuesday morning at <ORGANIZATION> Universal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>, said police Lt. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON>. The picket was released on $ 250 bail. A <PERSON> Cannell </PERSON> spokeswoman said production of the <ORGANIZATION> NBC-TV </ORGANIZATION> programs was suspended because tires were slashed or deflated on nine vehicles, a brake line was severed on a semi-trailer, holding tanks were punctured on a mobile dressing room, a trailer hitch was sabotaged and at least three employees were physically assaulted. Employees also received death threats and the company's <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> office received a bomb scare, said the spokeswoman, <PERSON> Lisa </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewinson </PERSON>. The office building, containing several hundred employees, was evacuated for more than two hours Monday, the first day of the strike. <PERSON> Lewinson </PERSON> said the company was `` outraged by the acts of violence, vandalism and threats to our employees and property.'' The studio planned to resume production `` as soon as possible with or without an end to the strike.'' A Teamster official denied that the union members had done anything illegal. `` All of the members were advised that they were to conduct themselves in a lawful manner,'' said <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Prelock </PERSON>, director of legal and contract affairs. `` We're going to do everything that's lawfully permissible and nothing more,'' he said. `` Sure, there's liable to be emotions. Hopefully, the reactions are simply that and nothing more. We are not personally aware of any physical violence.'' Teamsters pickets were stationed Tuesday at nearly every Hollywood studio. The Teamsters drivers, who transport actors, equipment and props for television and movie producers, picketed Monday at the <PERSON> Cannell </PERSON> offices and the outdoor productions of `` Sonny Spoon'' at an undisclosed location and of `` Hunter'' at the <LOCATION> Santa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Monica </LOCATION> pier. At the `` Hunter'' filming, some pickets blew air horns and banged on a trash container during scenes. Filming was delayed by more than an hour and the production closed earlier than scheduled Monday evening, <PERSON> Lewinson </PERSON> said. `` Hunter'' stars former pro football player <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> <PERSON> Dryer </PERSON> as a quick-witted detective; `` <PERSON> Sonny </PERSON> <PERSON> Spoon </PERSON>,'' an <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> adventure program, features <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> Peebles </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Cannell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> are named after producer-scriptwriter <PERSON> Stephen </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Cannell </PERSON>, who also created `` The Rockford Files'' and `` The A-Team.'' There have been other reported bomb threats related to the strike, said police Sgt. <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>. At least one other studio complained that some replacement drivers had been harassed by pickets. `` These actions will not be tolerated,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motion </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Picture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Producers </ORGANIZATION> said in a statement. The incidents `` are not only inappropriate, but perhaps illegal. ... We expect and demand that no further incidents take place. And we call on the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> to take appropriate action to ensure that their strike be conducted in a legal and nonviolent atmosphere.'' The strike against the 217-member alliance began early Monday after weekend negotiations collapsed. On Thursday, the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> voted 1,441-196 to reject the contract proposal submitted by the alliance. Unresolved issues include overtime rules for weekend work, salary rates, wages for out-of-town film and television production and guidelines for the making of nonunion films. Some drivers are being asked to take a pay cut from $ 16.61 to $ 14 per hour. Although the five-month strike by the 9,000-member <ORGANIZATION> Writers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guild </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> halted much of the industry's production, it never caused any the alliance members to close their doors and halt production.
