<TEXT>
 The dollar rose against major foreign currencies in quiet European trading today. Gold prices barely moved. Dealers said the dollar is in a moderate upward trend while the market waits for Friday's scheduled release of American unemployment figures for September. They said the figures will have no major impact on the dollar if they show, as expected, a slight decline from August's unemployment rate of 5.6 percent. `` There is no news to trade on,'' said one <LOCATION> Frankfurt </LOCATION> dealer. `` The market seems to be finished for the year.'' In <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, where trading ends as <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'s business day begins, the dollar rose 0.33 yen to a closing 133.48. Later, in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, it was quoted at 133.65 yen. Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Tuesday, were: _ 1.8655 West German marks, up from $ 1.8610 _ 1.5840 Swiss francs, up from $ 1.5775 _ 6.3540 French francs, up from $ 6.3285 _ 2.1027 Dutch guilders, up from $ 2.0950 _ 1,390.50 Italian lire, up from $ 1,385.875 _ 1.2080 Canadian dollars, down from $ 1.20965 In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, one British pound cost $ 1.6925, slightly cheaper for buyers than Currency dealers predicted the pound would soften because of nervousness following the government's decision Tuesday to order the <ORGANIZATION> Kuwait </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Investment </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> to reduce its stake in <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. PLC Gold opened in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> at a bid price of $ 397.50 a troy ounce, up from the $ 397.45 bid late Tuesday. At midmorning today, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $ 397.25 In <LOCATION> Zurich </LOCATION>, the bid price was $ 396.90, unchanged from late Tuesday. Earlier, in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>, gold fell $ 1.77 a t