<HEAD>U.S. Rep. MacKay Wins Democratic Race To Oppose Mack</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> `` Buddy'' <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON> said after winning the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> runoff that he would try to heal wounds from the divisive race while looking ahead to a `` mainstream versus extreme'' contest with Republican <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>. <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON> said he would meet in <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> today with state Insurance Commissioner <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>, the defeated <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> candidate who pledged to support <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON> less than a week after accusing the third-term congressman of running the nastiest campaign in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> history. Unofficial returns from Tuesday's runoff gave MacKay 362,234, or 52 percent of the vote, to <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>'s 330,297, or 48 percent. <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, a former Cape Coral bank president and grandson of the baseball Hall of Fame manager, is a well-funded conservative whose candidacy is drawing national Republican help. <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> and <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON> will face each other on the November ballot for the seat held by Democratic Sen. <PERSON> Lawton </PERSON> <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, who is retiring after three terms. `` We are the candidacy that can beat <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>,'' <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON> said Tuesday night. `` I see this election as mainstream versus extreme.'' <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> agreed that voters faced an ideological decision. `` I think the voters in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> are going to have a very clear choice between the liberal <PERSON> Buddy </PERSON> <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON> and the conservative <PERSON> Connie </PERSON> <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>,'' he said. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> runoff climaxed twisting events that began last December, when <PERSON> Chiles </PERSON>, 58, announced he would n't seek re-election, saying he was burned out by the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and did n't like the high cost of running for re-election. Popular former two-term Gov. <PERSON> Reubin </PERSON> <PERSON> Askew </PERSON> then entered the race against <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>. But <PERSON> Askew </PERSON>, well ahead in all polls, withdrew May 7, saying he did n't like all the time spent raising funds. <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON> and MacKay jumped in after <PERSON> Askew </PERSON> pulled out, and they ran one-two in the Sept. 6 primary. But neither received a majority, making a runoff necessary. <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON>, a lawyer from a wealthy landowning family, was endorsed by <PERSON> Askew </PERSON>, 1986 Democratic gubernatorial nominee <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Pajcic </PERSON>, third-place primary finisher Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mica </PERSON> and fourth-place finisher state Sen. <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON> <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>. The runoff campaign was filled with negative advertising and sharp exchanges in debates, and Democratic officials worried that <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> would face a crippled opponent in the general election. <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON>, 55, attacked <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>'s integrity for his practice each election of using campaign contributions from the insurance industry he regulates, including from two companies that later collapsed in corruption. He also charged that <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON> voted against desegregation 15 years ago. <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>, 54, charged that <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON>'s congressional record betrayed <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>, Social Security and anti-drug efforts, and he claimed <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON> was being supported by corrupt defense contractors. <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON> warned that the well-funded <PERSON> Mack </PERSON> could exploit <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON>'s alleged ethics problems <PERSON> Mack </PERSON>, meanwhile, went on the attack against <PERSON> MacKay </PERSON>, running television and newspaper ads charging: `` Hey Buddy, You're liberal!'' <PERSON> Gunter </PERSON> lost a 1974 Democratic <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> runoff and won a 1980 <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> runoff only to lose in the general election.
