<HEAD>Cinematographer Lucien Ballard Dies At 84</HEAD>
<DATELINE>RANCHO MIRAGE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Cinematographer <PERSON> Lucien </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON>, whose high-contrast imagery brought a sharp edge to such films as `` True Grit'' and `` The Wild Bunch,'' died of injuries from a traffic accident. He was 84. <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> died Saturday at <ORGANIZATION> Eisenhower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, two days after he collided with a tractor while riding his bicycle near his home, his son, <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON>, said Tuesday. The <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> native, whose career spanned nearly 50 years, shot more than 100 films, ranging from such serious efforts as `` The Caretakers'' for which he was nominated for an Academy Award, to two-reel comedies starring The Three Stooges. One of <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION>'s most distinguished cameramen, he worked with such directors as <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Peckinpah </PERSON>, <PERSON> Stanley </PERSON> <PERSON> Kubrick </PERSON>, <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hathaway </PERSON>, <PERSON> Dorothy </PERSON> <PERSON> Arzner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Josef </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Sternberg </PERSON>. But despite an illustrious career, <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> never received the industry's top honor, the Academy Award. Although nominated for `` The Caretakers'' in 1963, he lost to <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Wong </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> for `` Hud.'' Two of his most renowned Westerns, <PERSON> Peckinpah </PERSON>'s `` The Wild Bunch,'' and <PERSON> Hathaway </PERSON>'s `` True Grit,'' were both filmed in 1969. Some in <LOCATION> Hollywood </LOCATION> believed they may have canceled each other out in the Oscar race for best cinematography that year. `` True Grit'' garnered a best actor Oscar for <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Wayne </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> was planning to go into the lumber business when he discovered moviemaking after a script girl he was dating took him to a three-day party whose host was actress Clara Bow. Soon thereafter he visited Paramount studios, landing a job as a film cutter. He gained <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Sternberg </PERSON>'s attention while working as an assistant camera operator, and the director used him on his 1930 film `` <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>,'' starring <PERSON> Marlene </PERSON> <PERSON> Dietrich </PERSON>. <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> also worked with <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Sternberg </PERSON> on `` The Devil Is a Woman'' and `` Crime and Punishment.'' <PERSON> Ballard </PERSON> married actress <PERSON> Merle </PERSON> <PERSON> Oberon </PERSON> in 1945, but the couple divorced four years later.
