Premier <PERSON> Milos </PERSON> <PERSON> Milosavljevic </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> president <PERSON> Dusan </PERSON> <PERSON> Popovski </PERSON>, who has said he may resign. <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> is facing increasing labor and social unrest in the worst economic crisis in its postwar history. The foreign debt is $ 21 billion, unemployment is at least 15 percent and the official inflation rate has reached 217 percent. However, it is widely believed the inflation rate is actually higher. Two top <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leaders resigned last week from the 23-member ruling Presidium in reaction to mass rallies organized by <PERSON> Milosevic </PERSON> supporters in <LOCATION> Serbia </LOCATION>, the largest of <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>'s six republics. <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Stipe </PERSON> <PERSON> Suvar </PERSON> announced Tuesday that up to one-third of the <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> may be replaced at a key meeting Oct. 17, where a major shakedown is expected over the party's failure to manage the economic, ethnic and political tensions in <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION> Party leaders also have been blamed for failing to stop tensions in the autonomous region of <LOCATION> Kosovo </LOCATION> between ethnic Albanians, who are Moslems, and the Christian Slavs.
