<HEAD>Space Shuttle In The Garage For Servicing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EDWARDS AIR FORCE BASE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> crews today prepared Discovery for its piggyback ride atop a jet to <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> and repaired minor damage suffered in the space shuttle's 65 orbits of <LOCATION> Earth </LOCATION>. `` The crews are working, and they will work round the clock until the orbiter leaves'' Saturday, said <PERSON> Ted </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayers </PERSON>, deputy site manager for the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aeronautics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Space </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Dryden </PERSON> Flight Research Facility here The spacecraft, which landed here Monday, had six heat-shield tiles gouged by debris, apparently during liftoff, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Talone </PERSON>, shuttle processing director. Workers also found some `` dings'' to a few of the hundreds of tiles that coat the shuttle, but detected no damage to the orbiter's brakes, landing gear or tires, <PERSON> Talone </PERSON> said. Discovery sat inside the 100-foot-tall `` mate-demate device,'' a shuttle garage where it is being serviced before its trip aboard a jet Saturday to its <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> launch site. Workers must deactivate fuel cells, photograph tile damage and replace gouged tiles, purge main engines and orbital maneuvering engines, and attach locks to prevent control flaps from fluttering during the piggyback flight. Discovery's mission was <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s first manned space mission since the Challenger tragedy in January 1986 that killed seven crew members. `` The vehicle looks beautiful,'' <PERSON> Talone </PERSON> said during a news conference Tuesday. `` It looks probably as good or better as any vehicle we've brought in here.'' Six tiles near the right wing must be replaced because of a 12-inch-long, 6-inch-wide, 1 -LCB- - inch-deep gouge apparently caused by debris during the shuttle's launch Thursday, <PERSON> Talone </PERSON> said <PERSON> Talone </PERSON> said officials were n't yet sure if the debris was ice that formed on the outside of the shuttle's external tank, which contains supercold fuel. `` There's a minor number of traditional dings'' on some other tiles, caused by the impact of tiny particles during liftoff and landing, he added. After preliminary inspection found no damage, the shuttle's brakes were shipped to <PERSON> B.F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodrich </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> for a closer look, he said The brakes were improved because of brake and tire damage during previous missions. <PERSON> Talone </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> workers have n't identified the cause of the trouble with <ORGANIZATION> Discovery </ORGANIZATION>'s flash evaporators _ a problem that made the astronauts endure temperatures in the 80s during their flight. <ORGANIZATION> NASA </ORGANIZATION> plans for Discovery to depart <PERSON> Edwards </PERSON> early Saturday, arriving at Kennedy Space Center in <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> before dark following a single stop near <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Antonio </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Talone </PERSON> said. Discovery's next mission is scheduled to start Feb. 18, three months after <ORGANIZATION> Atlantis </ORGANIZATION>' planned Nov. 17 liftoff with a classified <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> payload.
