<BYLINE>By DALIA BALIGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A small group of top officials today attended a low-key military parade, the first since President <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> was assassinated, to mark the 15th anniversary of the 1973 Middle East War. <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> was killed at a much more elaborate anniversary parade on Oct. 6, 1981. President <PERSON> Hosni </PERSON> <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>, government ministers and a select group of diplomats were the only spectators allowed inside the high walls of the <ORGANIZATION> Military </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> for today's two-hour parade, broadcast live on television and radio. The government did not say why it held the parade a day earlier than the anniversary of the war's start. <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> considers its crossing of the <ORGANIZATION> Suez </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> on Oct. 6, 1973, and capture of <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> positions on the western side as its finest modern-day military accomplishment. The government also did not say why it resumed the military parade, an annual tradition under <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>. It was suspended after Moslem extremists killed the president and seven other people. Under <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>, the parades were held on one of <LOCATION> Cairo </LOCATION>'s largest streets. The day he died, he wore a white, high-booted uniform with gold braid. <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON>, commander of the air force before <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> chose him as vice president, stood beside him in uniform. <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> has not worn his uniform in public since that day. Today, he wore a dark blue suit and mirrored sunglasses. In <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON>'s parades, hundreds of gleaming tanks and armored personnel carriers filled the streets and jet fighter-bombers gave spectacular aerial shows. Today, trailers carrying tanks passed the elevated presidential box one at a time. A handful of helicopters with <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION>'s flag dangling from them flew overhead for a while, and 15 parachutists landed on the wide parade grounds. The parade was mainly a show of the weapons that <LOCATION> Egypt </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> used in the 1973 war, called the Yom Kippur War in <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> and the 10th of Ramadan War in the Arab world. In a brief videotaped address, <PERSON> Mubarak </PERSON> said <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> was a brave hero who decided to make war and won, then decided to make peace. <PERSON> Sadat </PERSON> and former Israeli Prime Minister <PERSON> Menachem </PERSON> <PERSON> Begin </PERSON>, spurred by President <PERSON> Carter </PERSON>, signed the Camp David accord in 1979. It is still the only peace agreement between an Arab country and the Jewish state.
