<HEAD>Chileans Decide Their Future, Pinochet's Fate</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with heavy turnout, Pinochet
quotes. Pick up 8th pvs, `If a...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN NOBLET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Thousands of troops guarded polling places today and voters stood in mile-long lines to cast `` yes'' or `` no'' ballots on a proposal to extend President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s 15-year rule to 1997 Power outages blamed on terrorist bombings plunged the capital and other cities into darkness late Tuesday, but the country was calm as polls opened at 8 a.m. By midmorning, thousands of voters lined up at <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> voting centers, waiting patiently under a sunny, cloudless sky in warm spring weather. <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s 7.4 million registered voters are required by law to vote. Some voters said they arrived early for fear of trouble later in the day. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who voted downtown late this morning, spoke sarcastically of the blackout by using the slogan of the opposition: `` It's the joy that's coming.'' But the 72-year-old army commander told reporters he heard no reports of incidents in the first hours of voting. `` There are no problems,'' he said. `` The people are voting normally.'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who campaigned hard across the country for a `` yes'' vote, was asked about the outcome and said, `` I'm always optimistic.'' Among early voters was <PERSON> Patricio </PERSON> <PERSON> Aylwin </PERSON>, president o the centrist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and leader of a 16-party coalition campaigning for <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s defeat. `` It's like returning to the times of the republic,'' he declared after casting his ballot in <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s first presidential vote since 1970. The downtown was virtually deserted, with shops and offices closed for election day, a national holiday. Radio reports also indicated a heavy turnout without serious problems in provincial cities and towns. If a majority votes `` yes,'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> will assume a new eight-year term in March. If most vote `` no,'' an open election with two or more candidates will take place next year, and the winner will assume the presidency in March 1990. At least eight explosions were heard in <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION> on Tuesday night, moments after the power outage affected a 1,300-mile stretch of the country. Police said terrorists bombed at least three electrical towers, but said they had no reports of damage or injuries from the subsequent explosions, indicating they may have been noise bombs intended to frighten but not harm. The nation's long-idled election machinery was put back in place for the referendum on <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>, who lifted emergency rule and loosened his tight grip on the opposition in the months preceding the balloting. The first unofficial returns are to be released about an hour after polls close at 5 a.m. The opposition coalition, distrustful of the <ORGANIZATION> Interior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION>'s tabulations, planned a separate vote count The group says it will accept as official the results of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electoral </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, which are to be disclosed on Friday. Gen. <PERSON> Jorge </PERSON> <PERSON> Zincke </PERSON>, military commander of <LOCATION> Santiago </LOCATION>, said officials were ordered to provide access at polling places to an estimated 500 foreign observers. `` We have nothing to hide,'' he said. About 150,000 members of the armed forces and national police have been on barracks alert since Sunday. If <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s new eight-year term is approved, the military junta he leads, which theoretically served as the legislative branch of his government, will be disbanded. A new <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would be seated in 1990, with two-thirds elected and the remaining third appointed by <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>. Whatever the outcome of the referendum, congressional elections will be held in 1990, but the legislature will have limited authority. It will be virtually powerless to amend a 1980 constitution, which gives the military autonomy and a supervisory role in national policy-making. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> has pointed to an improved economy and the promise of growth and stability if he is retained as president. His critics say the rich have benefited the most and that human rights abuses continue under his rule. About 3 million of the 7.4 million voters were too young to vote in 1973, when <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> led a bloody coup that toppled the elected government of President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Allende </PERSON>, a Marxist. <PERSON> Allende </PERSON> died in the coup. In 1978, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s military government won a vote of confidence and in 1980, it won passage the a new constitution. But both ballots were loosely organized, with no formal voter registration and few if any protections against fraud, which opposition groups say was widespread. This time, the opposition has expressed satisfaction with the safeguards.
