<HEAD>Judge Convicted, Two Acquitted in Corruption Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A judge was convicted of accepting bribes but a retired judge and an attorney were acquitted of related charges resulting from Operation Greylord, an extensive investigation of court corruption. Tuesday's acquittals were only the second and third acquittals in more than four years of trials resulting from the probe. So far, 90 judges, lawyers and other court employees have been indicted and 70 have been convicted, including 14 judges. Two people have died while awaiting trial, and the remaining cases are pending. Cook County Associate Judge <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Glecier </PERSON>, 60, was found guilty of one count of racketeering conspiracy. He was convicted of paying bribes as a defense attorney and accepting them as a judge. He will be stripped of his post and his $ 75,000 salary when he is sentenced Nov. 29. Former Cook County Judge <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> Maher </PERSON> and attorney <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Dineff </PERSON> were found innocent Tuesday.
