<DATELINE>BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Dr. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON>, an <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> physician who devoted his medical career to eradicating venereal diseases in the People's Republic of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, has died in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, state university officials said. <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON>, 78, who died Sunday, had been hospitalized since Aug. 4. He had been diagnosed as having cancer and diabetes. Once called the most beloved American in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, he is widely credited with ridding the world's most populous nation of most syphilis and gonorrhea, and he had hoped to eliminate leprosy from the country by the year 2000. In mainland <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> he was known as Dr. <PERSON> Ma </PERSON> <PERSON> Hai-teh </PERSON>, meaning `` virtue from overseas.'' During the 1950s, he became the first foreigner to become a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> citizen. Officials at the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION> said a cousin of <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON>'s, who had received a cable from the doctor's widow, informed them of his death Dr. <PERSON> Steven </PERSON> <PERSON> B </PERSON>. Sample, president of the university, presented <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> an honorary doctor of science degree last year in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. `` Over the past half-century, he led the fight against dreadful diseases like cholera, venereal disease and leprosy in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and in the process saved the lives of many millions of Chinese,'' Sample said. The son of <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> immigrants, <PERSON> Shafick </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> _ his first name was Americanized to <PERSON> George </PERSON> _ grew up in <LOCATION> Buffalo </LOCATION>. His medical career may have had its roots in an influenza epidemic in 1918, when his entire family was stricken. He recalled later how his family received care from a kindly doctor who made house calls and accepted no payment. With an undergraduate degree from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carolina </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> started his medical studies at the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and received his medical degree from the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Geneva </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. In 1933, he and two other doctors went to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> to study tropical diseases. <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> never came back. Shortly after his arrival in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> became friends with journalist <PERSON> Edgar </PERSON> <PERSON> Snow </PERSON>. When <PERSON> Mao </PERSON> <PERSON> Tse-tung </PERSON> became head of the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, he sent word to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> that he wanted a `` Western-trained doctor and an honest journalist.'' Snow and <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> managed to get through the Nationalist army lines to the Communists, where they first met <PERSON> Chou </PERSON> <PERSON> En-lai </PERSON>, then <PERSON> Mao </PERSON>. <PERSON> Hatem </PERSON> returned to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> when the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> took over <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> in 1949. As chief of staff of the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dermatology </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Venereology </PERSON>, he set up a patriotic health movement. His first targets were acute communicab