<HEAD>Scientists Trying New Products to Battle Grasshoppers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The age-old war against marauding grasshoppers is being waged with some promising new biological weapons, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. In one development, two commercial firms _ <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> BioControl </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Broomfield </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Bozeman </PERSON> Bio Tech of <PERSON> Bozeman </PERSON>, <PERSON> Mont </PERSON>. _ have adapted <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> technology for producing and storing a parasite, Nosema lucustae. Department studies show the parasite kills 50 percent to 60 percent of grasshoppers in three to four weeks. The basic tests and development were done by the department's <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> at the agency's <ORGANIZATION> Rangeland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Insect </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Laboratory </ORGANIZATION> in <PERSON> Bozeman </PERSON> by J.E <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> and colleagues. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said the parasite is available to homeowners and ranchers through regional agents and on contract to government agencies, which use it on a large scale in the West. <ORGANIZATION> Grasshoppers </ORGANIZATION> cause an estimated $ 400 million in damage to grass and crops each year, he said. Spores of the parasite are put on wheat bran flakes to form a bait. After the insects eat the bait, the organism `` attacks the pest's fat cells and depletes its energy stores,'' <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> said in a report issued here. The parasite remains in the grasshopper population because sick females pass it on to offspring, and survivors eat dead relatives, he said. Meanwhile, another development involves an agreement with <PERSON> Evans </PERSON> <PERSON> Biotechnical </PERSON> to field test another natural killer, grasshopper entomopoxvirus, the agency said. In laboratory tests, the virus kills 20 percent to 30 percent of the grasshoppers right away and stunts the growth of an additional 20 percent to 30 percent. <PERSON> Doug </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Streett </PERSON>, an entomoligist at the agency's <PERSON> Bozeman </PERSON> laboratory, said <ORGANIZATION> Evans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> BioControl </ORGANIZATION> plans to produce the virus and mix it with the parasite for tests on 1,000 acres in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Streett </PERSON> said that in combination the two ingredients may work more rapidly to kill the grasshoppers.
