<HEAD>Supreme Court Examines Affirmative Action Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES H. RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> heard arguments Wednesday that programs to reserve some public works contracts for minorities cause reverse discrimination, while proponents said they break down rigid racial barriers. The justices explored the power of state and local governments to give preferential treatment to minority-owned businesses in a key affirmative action case from <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, to be decided by July. At stake could be set-aside programs adopted by most states and some 190 local governments. The <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> plan was intended to fight racial discrimination, `` a scourge of our society,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Payton </PERSON>, a lawyer representing the city. Black participation in the construction trades had been `` close to zero,'' he said. `` The evidence is stark and dramatic'' that blacks were excluded systematically from entering and advancing in the industry. `` Other remedies had no impact. They simply were n't working,'' he added. But <PERSON> Walter </PERSON> <PERSON> Ryland </PERSON>, representing building contractor J.A. <ORGANIZATION> Croson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, said setting aside part of the contracts for minorities is reverse discrimination. `` If -LRB- city officials -RRB- wanted to attack societal discrimination, they could do it by racially neutral means,'' he said. <PERSON> Croson </PERSON> successfully challenged the set-aside after the company lost a city contract for failure to include a minority-owned business as a subcontractor. The 4th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled in September 1987 there is insufficient evidence that city officials discriminated against minority-owned businesses in the past and it said the plan's quota appeared to be completely arbitrary. <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> adopted the plan in 1983 to require that a prime contractor on any city building project subcontract at least 30 percent of the value of the project to firms that are at least one-half minority owned. While the minorities named in the plan include Hispanics, Orientals, Indians, Eskimos and Aleuts, the primary beneficiary would be blacks _ who make up around half of <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>'s black population. The <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> has been closely divided on affirmative action disputes, and Wednesday's hour-long argument session provided few hints on the likely outcome of the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> case. Justice <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, the court's newest member and possibly the key to the outcome of the case, pressed the lawyers on both sides to explain their positions. `` Is -LRB- the set-aside -RRB- the most narrowly tailored remedy'' for racial bias, he asked? <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> suggested that the quota could mean higher costs for city projects. <PERSON> Payton </PERSON> replied `` there is no real constitutional question'' posed by that possibility. `` <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> can decide that is the cost of remedying'' past discrimination. <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, participating in his first affirmative action case since joining the court last February, replaced Justice <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Powell </PERSON>, who often cast the deciding vote on programs involving preferential treatment for minorities. The <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> case also may help foretell the court's future approach to other forms of affirmative action and alleged reverse discrimination. The justices in a recent string of decisions generally have upheld preferential treatment for minorities and women. <ORGANIZATION> Ryland </ORGANIZATION> challenged <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION>'s motives in adopting the set-aside policy. Noting that the city council had a black majority and that the city's population is around 50 percent black, he said the plan `` could be just a pork-barrel thing.'' But Chief Justice <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> H. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> noted that the court in 1980 upheld a similar 10 percent quota adopted by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> for federal building contracts. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> also might adopt pork-barrel legislation, <PERSON> Rehnquist </PERSON> said, `` but we give it a presumption of validity.'' How <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> selected a 30 percent quota is one of the issues at the heart of the case. <ORGANIZATION> Ryland </ORGANIZATION> said the figure was `` pulled out of the air'' and was `` so high it can force a particularly serious impact on non-minorty firms.'' But <PERSON> Payton </PERSON> said 30 percent is a reasonable compromise in a city that is half black and where historically minority-owned businesses received less than 1 percent of the value of city contracts. Set-aside programs also have caused some deep divisions and seemingly contradictory views within the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>, for example, said in 1984 he favored channeling billions of additional contract dollars to minority-owned firms. And the administration generally has looked upon public works set-asides more sympathetically than other affirmative action quotas it sternly opposes. But the <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, responding to an invitation from the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> in a case similar to the <LOCATION> Richmond </LOCATION> dispute, challenged the constitutionality of set-asides.
