<HEAD>Environment Group Sues Government to Halt CFC Production</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An environmental group said Wednesday it had sued the <ORGANIZATION> Environmental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Protection </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> seeking to force it to order a complete end to the use of chemicals that destroy the earth's protective ozone layer. The suit by the <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Defense </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> challenges the adequacy of the partial cutbacks that <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> ordered for five major chlorofluorocarbon compounds, or <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s, on Aug. 1. Those regulations paralled provisions of the 1987 treaty by major producing nations pledging themselves to a 50 percent reduction in <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> output by 1998. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> Administrator <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> last week said new analyses show that the 50 percent cut will not protect the ozone layer high in the stratosphere and the chemicals in question should be phased out. The ozone layer reduces the amount of cancer-causing ultraviolet rays from the sun that reach the earth's surface. The <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION> compounds, normally inert, rise through the atmosphere to the ozone layer, where those same ultraviolet rays break them apart and free chlorine to destroy the ozone. <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s are used as refrigeration fluids, solvents and plastic foam blowing agents. Many countries still permit their use as aerosol propellants, a use banned in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> in 1978. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is the single largest contributor to world-wide emissions of ozone-depleting chemicals,'' responsible for about 30 percent of global use, said <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON>, an attorney for the council. `` We have a responsibility to clean up our own house.'' <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON> argued that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` leads best when it leads by example.'' He said the <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> could pressure other countries to follow suit by banning imports of products made with <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s unless the importing country also was committed to ending CFC use. He said <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION>'s refusal to go beyond the treaty in its regulations `` appears to reflect a deal struck within the administration last summer'' to placate a faction that believed no treaty was necessary. <ORGANIZATION> EPA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Dave </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said <PERSON> Doniger </PERSON>'s `` notion of a deal is untrue and silly.'' `` Our goal all along has been to get the nations of the world to the table and agree to the deepest reductions we could possibly get,'' <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. `` We feel only a global solution will truly help the ozone layer,'' and unilateral <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> action could be counterproductive by leading other nations to conclude they could safely increase their use of <ORGANIZATION> CFC </ORGANIZATION>'s as a result, <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON> said. The suit was filed in the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>.
