<FIRST>r w AM-Incontinence     10-05 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Incontinence,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Says Doctors Can Do More To Help Incontinence Sufferers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Ten million Americans suffer from urinary incontinence and most could be helped if doctors would apply proven treatments in more cases, a <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> committee concluded Wednesday. `` We're not talking about rocket science here,'' said Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>, chairman of the 15-member consensus development panel. `` This is something we can do tomorrow.'' The committee report calls for family physicians to pay more attention to incontinence problems in their elderly patients and educate themselves about threatment. It also urges patients to be more assertive in expecting adequate treatment if they are incontinent. And it called for more research into the causes of incontinence, a field the experts said has largely been overlooked in the quest for answers to more exotic medical ailments. Their fundamental point, however, was that the existing treatments often do not get to the people who need them because of a widespread and erroneous belief, even by many doctors, that incontinence is a natural consequence of aging. `` This is an issue we can no longer neglect,'' <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON> said at a news conference wrapping up the panel's three-day meeting. `` Most cases can be cured or improved.'' He said more than half of those suffering from the problem are not even evaluated, let alone treated. <PERSON> Rowe </PERSON>, a professor from <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mount </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sinai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, offered this hypothetical remark from doctor to incontinent patient as all too familiar: `` Well, what do you expect, my dear. After all, you are 82.'' He said the patient should reply: `` I expect to get responsible, adequate medical care.'' One specific recommendation was for legislation requiring the manufacturers of adult diapers to carry a label message emphasizing that most incontinence is treatable and that anyone suffering from it should get a full medical evaluation. `` Many people with incontinence turn prematurely to the use of absorbent materials without having their difficult properly diagnosed and treated,'' the report said. There are several treatments for the various causes of incontinence, which is defined in the report as `` a symptom rather than a disease.'' The condition can be treated with drugs, surgery or behavioral techniques, which include exercises and biofeedback.
