<FIRST>r w AM-Scotus-Sentencing     10-05 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scotus-Sentencing,620</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lawyer Questions Constitutionality of New Sentencing System</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD CARELLI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A lawyer urged the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday to strike down a new sentencing system for people convicted of federal crimes, saying, `` Judges are supposed to stay out of political controversies.'' <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> attacked federal sentencing rules that took effect last Nov. 1 because the seven-member commission that issued them included three federal judges. Judges participating in a political process `` that could fairly be called horse-trading'' is unconstitutional because it impugns the federal judiciary's neutrality and impartiality, <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> argued. The job of passing laws about sentences for federal crimes belongs to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and not to judges, <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> said. But Solicitor General <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Fried </PERSON>, the government's top courtroom lawyer, called the <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Sentencing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>'s work a constitutionally acceptable attempt to resolve `` grave, invidious and inexplicable disparities in the sentencing process.'' At issue is the validity of the commission, created by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, and the validity of the sentencing rules it issued. More than 90 federal trial judges have refused to use the new sentencing rules, declaring them and the commission unconstitutional. But at least 60 of their colleagues have upheld the system, imposing sentences under the new rules. By the time the justices announce their decision, expected by July, thousands of defendants will be subject to resentencing _ regardless of which way the court rules. If the justices uphold the system, those defendants sentenced by judges who refused to apply the new rules will have to be resentenced. If the justices invalidate the system, those defendants sentenced under the new rules will have to be resentenced. The commission estimated that by Jan. 1, more than 10,000 federal court defendants will have been subjected to the new sentencing system. <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> created the commission in the Sentencing Reform Act of 1984, legislation aimed at eliminating what some called unjustified disparities in sentences. The law empowers the commission _ with its members appointed to six-year terms by the president _ to tell federal judges what sentences should be imposed for various crimes. The rules generally stiffened the prison time federal convicts were required to serve. They also eliminated parole and curtailed credit for good behavior. <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON>, representing a man who pleaded guilty in federal court to conspiring to possess and distribute cocaine, argued that `` the laying down of broad rules causes -LRB- the three commission member -RRB- judges to be embroiled in political controversy.'' `` Judges appointed for life must maintain their neutrality and impartiality,'' <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> said. Fried acknowledged that having judges serve on the commission raises certain `` policy concerns,'' but said those concerns `` have no grounding as constitutional prohibitions.'' Several members of the court, most persistently Justices <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> and <PERSON> Antonin </PERSON> <PERSON> Scalia </PERSON>, asked Fried questions that appeared to challenge his assertion of the commission's constitutionality. Representing the commission, <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> lawyer <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bator </PERSON> said the constitutionally required separation of the political branches does not bar <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> from establishing an independent agency to make laws about sentencing. He said <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> could give the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> the same authority over federal sentencing without any constitutional violation. The test case before the justices stems from the prosecution of <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mistretta </PERSON>, who pleaded guilty to conspiring to possess and distribute cocaine after his arrest last year in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>. Before <PERSON> Mistretta </PERSON>'s sentence was imposed, he challenged the new sentencing rules. A trial judge dismissed the challenge and sentenced <PERSON> Mistretta </PERSON> to 18 months in prison, to be followed by a three-year term of supervised release. <PERSON> Mistretta </PERSON> then appealed to the 8th <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION>, but the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> granted Fried's request that it decide the constitutional issue while the case is pending before the appeals court. The case is <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> vs. <PERSON> Mistretta </PERSON>, 87-1904.
