<FIRST>r w AM-HazardousMail     10-05 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hazardous Mail,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Germ Mail Ban Draws Opposition</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A proposal to ban the mailing of germs and dangerous toxins has drown vigorous opposition, Assistant Postmaster General <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Heselton </PERSON> said Wednesday. As a result, final action on the ban has been postponed until the issue can be more fully studied, <PERSON> Heselton </PERSON> reported to a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Civil </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> subcommittee. And, <PERSON> Heselton </PERSON> said, the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> has contacted the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> for assistance in developing safety standards for hazardous mail. Of 508 comments received after the proposed rule was made public, only seven favored the ban, <PERSON> Heselton </PERSON> said. Opposition, for various reasons, came from doctors, laboratories, colleges and universities, medical centers, pathologists and biologists and state and federal health groups, among others, he said. The plan to exclude germs and toxins from the mail was announced in June in the wake of reports that the military had increased shipments of such items. The action was taken `` to ensure the safety and health of ... customers and employees,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said in announcing the decision. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is concerned that some customers are planning increased use of the mails for sending disease germs or hazardous toxins -LRB- etiologic agents -RRB-.'' Opponents of the restriction contended that there is no record of anyone ever being infected by handling mailed germs or toxins, however. They said the ban would increase the costs of shipping medical materials for testing purposes, possibly slow down such testing and might lead mailers to improperly package and misidentify such items in order to mail them. The <ORGANIZATION> Postal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> does not want to increase medical costs or have a negative impact on medical diagnosis or research, <PERSON> Heselton </PERSON> said, but it must also be able to protect both its employees and the public. `` It may be possible to reduce the risk by reducing the quantity permitted for medical purposes per parcel, and requiring better packaging and more expeditious means of movement in the mail,'' he said. Postal workers in <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> last year expressed concern about blood and other medical samples mailed to a laboratory there for testing, when some packages were found leaking. Mail handlers were supplied with gloves, masks and other protective gear at the time, and the packaging for the samples has since been improved. Postal regulations already prohibit the mailing of a variety of items, including strike-anywhere matches, explosives, fuses, many poisons, most flammable liquids and certain chemicals. Many other items, such as corrosives, compressed gases, herbicides, pesticides and certain other poisons, can be mailed only in certain types of packages and in specific quantities.
</TEXT>
