<HEAD>Casket Race Will Lay to Rest Any Doubts About Town's Spirit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOYT HARWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOODWATER, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 This town's casket race is such a `` monumental'' effort, <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Darling </PERSON> says, that it took five years to put together a second one. Now, the caskets and contestants are ready for the race Saturday over a 75-yard obstacle course, said the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Rotary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> in this town of 2,000, about 250 of whom work at <ORGANIZATION> Goodwater </ORGANIZATION>'s three casket manufacturers Darling said each casket will contain one `` live corpse'' borne by six pallbearers who will have to run around two tombstones, through a pit called a grave, over sawdust called grave dust and through cross ties and auto tires. The person in each casket will carry a cup of water in a two-cup measuring container. If an ounce or more is spilled, the team is disqualified. Two first-place prizes are $ 140 and a trophy shaped like a casket. If the two of the 20 or so teams finish in a `` dead heat,'' the prize will be shared. Goodwater's casket manufacturers will provide their wares for the race. `` They are major industries and we want to show appreciation to them,'' said Darling, a pharmacist. As was done before the first race, in 1983, a casket promoting the event is on display at a service station in the heart of town. `` We hold our fall festival every year, but the casket race is such a ` monumental' effort for so many people we could n't ` handle' it every year,'' <PERSON> Darling </PERSON> said He said the town's casket business `` is pretty much booming. People are dying to get one.''
