ich effectively separates East and West. `` We are disappointed by the Soviets' unconstructive approach to the initiative,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Oakley </PERSON> said. `` They must understand that progress in <LOCATION> East-West </LOCATION> relations can not bypass <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>, and that stability in and around the city can only be maintained over time by taking steps to meet the legitimate aspirations of Berliners for positive change.'' She said the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would continue to press for progress on the initiative and its goals. `` I am not going to get into the details of their communication this,'' the spokeswoman said of the Sept. 15 Soviet response. `` Obviously, we feel that it was not forthcoming. But we're going to continue to press them on it.''
