<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Hundreds of youths rioting against inflation virtually took over the capital's central district Wednesday, setting cars ablaze and breaking shop windows while police looked on, witnesses reported. The rioters, mostly schoolboys and university students, were protesting a constantly increasing cost of living and consequent reductions in real wages. <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> has been hit by several strikes recently and new ones were reported Wednesday at the offices of the carrier <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Algerie </ORGANIZATION>, the post office and in various industries. Gangs of several hundred youngsters were seen overturning cars and setting them afire on the main shopping streets, <PERSON> Didouche </PERSON> <PERSON> Mourad </PERSON> and <PERSON> Mohamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Ben </PERSON> <PERSON> M'Hidi </PERSON>. They broke windows of shops and government-owned department stores and attacked the information office of the Polisario independence movement of the <LOCATION> Western </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sahara </LOCATION>. Glass littered the streets for well over a mile. One group of rioters stopped a bus, made the driver get out and then broke all the windows, witnesses reported. The offices of the West German airline <ORGANIZATION> Lufthansa </ORGANIZATION> and the Czechoslovak airline CSA were wrecked, as were many shops that did not get their metal curtains down quickly. At the <ORGANIZATION> Lufthansa </ORGANIZATION> office, counters were overturned, reservation computers ripped out and documents scattered in the street. Rioters also invaded libraries, cafes and restaurants. A nightclub called `` Blue Note'' was destroyed. About 100 young rioters brought bottles from inside the club and used them as projectiles. Others carried the furniture from the government's <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publicity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> and set fire to it front of the central post office. Security forces did little to stop the rampage, but several vehicles carrying riot police with tear gas launchers took positions at midday around the main Air Algerie office near the lower end of <LOCATION> Didouche </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mourad </LOCATION>. It office was not damaged. Young people were seen hurling stones at small groups of police in side streets. Workers who struck an auto parts factory in late September said they had not had a raise in years. Their strike led to a confrontation with police. Employees of the plant earn the equivalent of $ 270 - $ 330 a month while many prices have soared because of new government economic policies intended to `` rationalize consumption'' and encourage production Bread is subsidized and still sells for about 17 cents, but beef costs nearly $ 12 a pound. Strikers and protesters also complain of shortages. Butter, for example, has not been available for about a month. President <PERSON> Chadli </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendjedid </PERSON> says the reforms are necessary but his government announced Tuesday in conjunction with the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Algerian </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION>, the country's only labor union, that an effort would be made to provide more staples at lower prices.
