<HEAD>Report Urges Better Information Systems for Government</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The spread of electronic data systems poses the need for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to improve the way the government distributes information, the congressional <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assessment </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The report said existing laws and the government's methods for information dissemination, established by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> largely during the pre-electronic era, have been overtaken by technology. `` The government is at a crucial point where opportunities presented by the information technologies, such as productivity and cost-effectiveness improvements, are substantial,'' the agency said. Bibliographic, reference, statistical and scientific and technical information produced by the federal government is particularly well-suited to electronic formats. But the major federal information systems _ the <ORGANIZATION> Government </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Printing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> document sales program, the Depository Library Program and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> _ are limited largely to paper and microfiche. Full use of electronic technologies could help these agencies, <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> said. `` What <ORGANIZATION> OTA </ORGANIZATION> tells us in their report is that the methods we depend on to transmit information have reached their limits, and that new technologies are waiting to change the way government communicates,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Roe </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.J. </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION>, Space and Technology.
