<HEAD>U.N. Sources Say Iran Agrees To Stop Searching Ships In Persian
Gulf</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has agreed to stop searching ships in international waters of the <LOCATION> Persian </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Gulf </LOCATION> which it suspects of carrying war cargo to <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>, sources in the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> said Wednesday. The sources, speaking on condition of anonymity, also said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> agreed to postpone discussing ownership of the disputed Shatt-al-Arab waterway, <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s only outlet to the gulf. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> has a long gulf coastline with numerous ports. Breakthroughs on these two issues could help end the stalemate in the <LOCATION> Iran-Iraq </LOCATION> peace talks that began Aug. 25 in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>. The two neighbors in the oil-rich gulf, at war for eight years, agreed on Aug. 20 to a U.N.-sponsored truce. The sources said <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Secretary-General <PERSON> Javier </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> proposed the compromises during talks that began last week with the foreign ministers of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>. Those talks ended Wednesday. Under the proposals, <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> will no longer stop vessels flying a neutral flag in international gulf waters and the <LOCATION> Strait </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hormuz </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> consented to discuss its claims to <PERSON> Shatt-al-Arab </PERSON> later in the negotiations, the sources said. Both parties will begin arranging a withdrawal of their forces to the internationally recognized border and will discuss repatriation of prisoners of war, they added. No announcement of the compromise will be issued until peace talks resume in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION> later this month because <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> wants to wait and see if <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> honors the agreement, the sources said. In addition, <PERSON> Perez </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Cuellar </PERSON> and the Iranian and <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> diplomats agreed not to discuss details of their talks while progress is being made in negotiations between their lower-ranked representatives. <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s insistence that <PERSON> Shatt-al-Arab </PERSON> be cleared of sunken ships and dredged to remove silt has blocked progress in the talks. To be taken up later in the peace talks is the issue of whether both nations share rights to the waterway under a 1975 treaty or whether <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION> has sovereignty over the whole passage and both its banks, the sources reported. <LOCATION> Baghdad </LOCATION> also complained that <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>'s searching of ships for Iraq-bound war cargo violated a <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> resolution calling for the parties to `` discontinue all military activities on land, at sea and in the air.'' <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> held that searching for war cargo was a right that nations at war generally are recognized to have. The Iran-Iraq war broke out in September 1980 when <LOCATION> Iraqi </LOCATION> forces invaded western <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> after weeks of border skirmishes. More than 1 million casualties are estimated to have resulted from the war.
