<HEAD>Glaucoma Patient Complains of Slow Pot Permission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A glaucoma patient here complains she is going blind waiting for permission to legally use marijuana, and a federal official acknowledged Wednesday that the application procedure is complicated. <PERSON> Elvy </PERSON> <PERSON> Musikka </PERSON> was tried in August on charges of growing marijuana plants in her back yard. She and her physician successfully argued that using the drug was the only way to relieve glaucoma's pressure on her eyes. After her arrest, she applied to the <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> for a federal program to receive pot legally for medical treatments. That was six months ago. Tuesday she said she is already blind in the right eye, and slowly losing the remaining sight in her left eye waiting for her application to be processed. <PERSON> Faye </PERSON> <PERSON> Peterson </PERSON>, a spokeswoman for the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, said by law she can not discuss details of Ms. <PERSON> Musikka </PERSON>'s case. But she noted that even the <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enforcement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> is involved in clearing applications. `` It not only involves this agency, it involves the <ORGANIZATION> DEA </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Abuse </ORGANIZATION>,'' she said. `` It's not just a simple matter of saying, ` <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION>, give us permission.''' Appearing with Ms. <PERSON> Mussika </PERSON> at her news conference was stockbroker <PERSON> Irvin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rosenfeld </PERSON>, who suffers from a rare disease that causes tumors to grow in his bones. Marijuana enhances the medication he takes and helps ease the pain. He is one of only two <LOCATION> Broward </LOCATION> residents permitted to use the drug legally. `` I know how many hours it takes to fill out the paperwork,'' said <PERSON> Rosenfeld </PERSON>. `` This is how they put me off for 5 -LCB- years.'' Since her acquittal by <ORGANIZATION> Broward </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Judge </ORGANIZATION> <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Polen </PERSON>, Ms. <PERSON> Musikka </PERSON> said she has been getting marijuana when she can from friends. It's either that or lose her remaining sight, she said. `` Anyone that's helping me now is breaking the law,'' she said. `` They're human people, compassionate people who care.'' <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Randall </PERSON> is president of the <ORGANIZATION> Alliance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cannabis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Therapeutics </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based organization that helps people legally get marijuana for medical purposes. `` We are publicly watching a human being go blind because of an unresponsive federal government,'' said <PERSON> Randall </PERSON>, who won the legal right to use marijuana to treat his glaucoma 12 years ago. He said it could take a lawsuit against the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> to force action on Ms. <PERSON> Mussika </PERSON>'s application. Ms. <PERSON> Musikka </PERSON> was born with congenital cataracts and developed glaucoma as she grew up. Glaucoma, the leading cause of blindness in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, increases pressure on the eyeball and optic nerve and causes a progressive loss of sight.
