t seek confirmation, the <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> said. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> requires airplanes in the area to be separated a minimum of three miles horizontally and 1,000 feet vertically. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Bellino </PERSON>, regional representative of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Controllers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, said <LOCATION> O'Hare </LOCATION>'s radar room on Friday was `` a zoo.'' With Friday's 3,842 takeoffs and landings _ just below the all-time record of 3,853 set the day before _ there should have been 18 journeyman controllers and several `` developmental'' controllers on duty. Developmental controllers have fewer responsibilities than the journeymen. But <PERSON> Bellino </PERSON> said there were only 14 controllers working and the problem was made worse when the controllers who made the errors were temporarily relieved of their duties, giving those who remained even more responsibilities. The <ORGANIZATION> FAA </ORGANIZATION> could not immediately say how many controllers were on duty Friday, but <PERSON> Zochert </PERSON> said the number of controllers working at the airport has risen from 87 last year to 94 as of Sept. 1.
