<TEXT>
 Scientists, scholars, writers and artists from countries with restricted freedom of expression will work at 15 American colleges under a program established by the <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION>, sponsors said Wednesday. <PERSON> Miklos </PERSON> <PERSON> Haraszti </PERSON>, a dissident writer from <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, arrived at <ORGANIZATION> Bard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Annandale-on-Hudson </LOCATION> in September, becoming the first fellow of the International Academy for Scholarship and the Arts. The <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> has given a $ 100,000 grant to establish the program, said <PERSON> Leon </PERSON> <PERSON> Botstein </PERSON>, president of <ORGANIZATION> Bard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION>, which will serve as its administrator. The fellows will reside for at least one academic year at the American colleges, pursuing their work while teaching. `` Serious and gifted scholars and artists from all over the world who need the opportunity to think, study, investigate and write without restriction will be served,'' said <PERSON> Botstein </PERSON>. `` In return, our students, faculty and staff can only benefit by their presence.'' The sponsors said applicants for the fellowship will most likely be among three categories: _ Emigrant artists and intellectuals who are living in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> or the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> but who are unemployed or underemployed _ Individuals who seek to leave their homeland, perhaps permanently, as a matter of conscience _ Individuals who would like to come to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> but who intend to return to their homeland, despite any political or economic pressures that may await them The program also will include <ORGANIZATION> Dartmouth </ORGANIZATION> <