<HEAD>Bush Calls for Programs to Help Families, Environment</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: To UPDATE with Bush reaction to opening of debate, INSERTS 1
graf after 10th pvs, editing 11th pvs appropriately, picking up
11th pvs bgng ``Bush also ...''</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Wednesday proposed a $ 3.9 billion `` invest in our children'' plan focusing on school programs and environmental and quality-of-life issues <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said will foster stronger children through `` a family that functions and an environment that motivates.'' The package, including some proposals <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has made before, would be aimed at helping poor people through tax code revisions and Medicaid efforts, and would also include anti-crime and anti-gang sections as well as efforts to remove toxic substances from school environments. A 32-page summary released by the Republican's presidential campaign also includes proposals to require Medicaid coverage for poor children and to give the states $ 10 million for developing programs against hazardous radon gas. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called for a national survey of schools in 1990 to detect and get rid of radon, and also for `` strict standards'' covering manufacturers who use lead in development of consumer products. Although <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said in a remark at a <ORGANIZATION> Arapahoe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> High </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> that `` I do n't see this problem in terms of money,'' campaign adviser <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Steelman </PERSON> said the entire package would cost about $ 3.9 billion in federal money for the first year of a five-year plan. Included in that figure is a previously announced $ 2.2 billion tax credit program for child care. <PERSON> Steelman </PERSON> said the new Medicaid proposals would amount to some $ 300 million. `` Why are some children still in trouble after 50 years of liberal programs aimed at helping them?'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> asked. `` Because liberalism did n't help _ it often made the problem worse.'' The vice president took some time out from his campaign duties to telephone running mate <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and wish him well in his debate Wednesday night with Democrat <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, according to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s chief of staff <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON>. During the 10-minute conversation, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, `` Relax, I know it will go well.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has been favorably impressed with <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said. `` When the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people get a chance to see the <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> we know they will all be favorably impressed,'' <PERSON> Fuller </PERSON> said. The vice president watched the debate from <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Worth </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>. `` He's doing good, good opening, right out of the ball park, the <PERSON> Canseco </PERSON> of American politics,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, referring to <LOCATION> Oakland </LOCATION> A's baseball player <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Canseco </PERSON> in describing <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>'s response to the first question of the debate to a group of reporters he had invited to watch the opening of the event `` He hit it the first answer, home run.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also traveled Wednesday to <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, where the oil industry is struggling through tough times. `` You're back,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> told a rally. `` <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> is coming strong.'' Promising to decontrol natural gas, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is an opponent of the energy industry but `` is now trying to fool the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people by acting like he cares about the energy industry.'' At the high school in the <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Littleton </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said, `` Our future will be as strong tomorrow as our children are today. And our children will be as strong as their education allows. Their eduction will be as strong as their schools. But something more is required: a family that functions and an environment that motivates.'' Included in the plan is a call to phase in affordable Medicaid coverage for pregnant women and infants with incomes up to 185 percent of the poverty level. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also would expand on current Medicaid coverage for children of families with incomes below the poverty level by providing health-care education for those families. The proposals were an elaboration on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s remarks in his first debate with Democratic rival <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> that he wanted to allow the poor to `` buy into'' Medicaid, said <PERSON> Steelman </PERSON>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said he would also expand the Maternal and Child Health Block Grant program to provide health and Medicaid information for pregnant women and provide case management `` as an essential component for high risk in teen-age pregnancies that are likely to result in low birth weight.'' He also called for mandatory Medicaid coverage `` of functionally disabled children who would have to be in a hospital or other institution without such coverage for home care.'' In other areas, he called for: _ Mandatory child support levels and enforcement, and a `` nationwide parent locator system'' to track down delinquent parents. _ Case management and counseling to teach parents about health care and nutrition. _ Encouraging states to make drug testing a condition of bail, probation and parole. _ A focus on crime in the schools with creation of a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> anti-gang unit to work with local jurisdictions. _ Legislation to give the federal government concurrent jurisdiction over juveniles committing federal crimes, so that the federal government can act `` if the state fails to vigorously prosecute juveniles.'' _ Housing vouchers to get assistance to low-income families, a system he said would provide three times as much assistance as building housing for the same price. In giving spending projections for the newly announced programs, <PERSON> Steelman </PERSON> said the anti-gang unit portion would run about $ 50 million, new Medicaid for mothers and infants at 185 percent of the poverty level would be $ 300 million with another $ 80 million for case management in Medicaid. The radon and lead programs would cost $ 30 million, and a program to help turn over subsudized housing to tenants would cost $ 80 million, she said.
