<HEAD>Teamster Harassment Blocked by Court Order</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Striking Hollywood drivers and three production companies agreed to an order Wednesday barring the drivers from intimidating studio employees and disrupting film and television production. To stem the increasingly violent atmosphere surrounding the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> strike, the <ORGANIZATION> Cannell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Lorimar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> MTM-CBS </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> joined in a temporary restraining order with the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> which was approved by <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> Judge <PERSON> Kurt </PERSON> <PERSON> Lewin </PERSON>. The <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> agreed to observe new rules about the size of picket contingents, how close they can come to studio gates and the distance between the marchers and the pace at which they walk so as to not obstruct traffic. The restrictions will be considered more fully at hearing Oct. 18. The walkout, affecting 3,200 drivers, laborers and electricians, began Monday. The <ORGANIZATION> Cannell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Studios </ORGANIZATION> closed down production on its shows `` Hunter'' and `` Sonny Spoon'' on Tuesday after a series of reports of violence, including death threats, physical assaults and slashed tires. Even as the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> and the producers met in court, there were more reports of confrontations. Location filming on the CBS series `` Murder, She Wrote'' was disrupted Wednesday when pickets encouraged passing motorists to honk their horns, according to security guard <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Loust </PERSON>. <PERSON> Loust </PERSON> said that several replacement drivers went home early because they were being harassed by pickets. Teamster officials did not respond to interview requests. The Teamster drivers transport actors, equipment and props for television and film producers. Joining the Teamsters on the picket lines are 1,000 members of two other Basic Crafts unions, the electricians and the laborers. The Hollywood plasterers and the plumbers, the remaining Basic Crafts guilds, are not on strike. Issues in the strike include overtime rules for weekend work, salary rates, wages for out-of-town film and television production, seniority and guidelines for the making of nonunion films. Some drivers are being asked to take a pay cut from $ 16.61 to $ 14 per hour. The producers maintain that the <ORGANIZATION> Teamsters </ORGANIZATION> must help manage mounting production costs and increased competition. Overall, the contract proposal represents an increase in employment and salaries, the producers say.
