<HEAD>`Killing Fields' Survivor Assails U.N. For Seating Khmer Rouge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> photographer <PERSON> Dith </PERSON> <PERSON> Pran </PERSON>, a survivor of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s killing fields, denounced the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday for letting the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> be part of the Cambodian <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> delegation. `` I am still shocked when I see the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> flag on <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> territory. How would you feel if you were Jewish and you saw <PERSON> Hitler </PERSON>'s flag flying at the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION>?'' <PERSON> Dith </PERSON> <PERSON> Pran </PERSON> asked a crowd of about 250 demonstrators at a vigil outside <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Headquarters. The <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION> toppled the U.S.-backed Cambodian government in 1975, trapping <PERSON> Dith </PERSON> <PERSON> Pran </PERSON> in his country. Like most of the population, he endured famine and forced labor on a collective farm, but escaped to <LOCATION> Thailand </LOCATION> in 1979 and from there joined his family in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dith </PERSON> <PERSON> Pran </PERSON>'s ordeal, and that of his people, were the focus of the film `` The Killing Fields.'' <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> delegation called Wednesday for <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s withdrawal from their country, and said a political solution to the nation's troubles must be based on national reconciliation among all parties, including the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>, which ruled until 1979 But Son <PERSON> Sann </PERSON>, prime minister of the governmen