000 of its 120,000 occupation troops from <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> this year, and all will be out by early 1990. Among those pessimistic about the future of <LOCATION> Cambodia </LOCATION> is <PERSON> Dith </PERSON> <PERSON> Pran </PERSON>'s friend, <PERSON> Sydney </PERSON> <PERSON> Schanberg </PERSON>, the Pulitzer Prize-winning former correspondent for <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Schanberg </PERSON> lingered almost unnoticed at Wednesday's vigil and declined to be interviewed, saying this was an occasion for the Cambodians to be heard. But he said he could not believe <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> would desert its longtime ally, the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. In the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Son </PERSON> <PERSON> Sann </PERSON> assailed <LOCATION> Vietnam </LOCATION>'s occupation forces Son <PERSON> Sann </PERSON>'s non-communist <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION>, and forces loyal to former Cambodian head of state Prince <PERSON> Norodom </PERSON> <PERSON> Sihanouk </PERSON> make up the U.N.-recognized delegation along with the <ORGANIZATION> Khmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rouge </ORGANIZATION>. Under the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> Charter and international law, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> says it can not recognize a government imposed on a country by outside force, such as the present Cambodian government installed by <LOCATION> Hanoi </LOCATION>.
