<FIRST>r i AM-Brazil     10-05 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bells Peal Across Brasilia As Brazil Enacts Eighth Constitution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Church bells rang in this modernistic capital Wednesday as <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> enacted its eighth constitution, consolidating the switchover from military rule to civilian government that began in 1985. The 559 legislators, who for 19 months battled over the 245-article document, cheered and shouted `` <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is changing!'' as the president of the <ORGANIZATION> Constituent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Ulysses </PERSON> <PERSON> Guimaraes </PERSON>, declared law the new document. `` I declare enacted the constitution of liberty, of dignity, of democracy and social justice,'' <ORGANIZATION> Guimaraes </ORGANIZATION>, 72, said in a voice that struggled above thunderous applause. `` May God help us enforce it.'' <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s new democratic charter leaves behind the old authoritarian document that was handed down by military generals in 1969. The enactment was the last step in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s return to fully democratic rule begun in March 1985, when <PERSON> Jose </PERSON> <PERSON> Sarney </PERSON> became <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s first civilian president since a 1964 right-wing military coup. `` We have created a new <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, a new social and economic order,'' <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Oliveira </PERSON> of the governing <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Movement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> said after the ceremony. `` We have taught the world an important lesson, peacefully overturning an authoritarian regime.'' The new document, a mixture of left-leaning, conservative and nationalistic articles that touch almost all aspects of life from land reform to interest rates, granted none of the arbitrary powers used by the repressive military government during 21 years to rule the country. The new charter bans censorship, removes the president's power to simply decree law and outlaws torture, which in the past was used against the military government's political opponents. But many of the articles were confusing. Several such as a reduced work week, more maternity leave and extra pay for overtime immediately became law; 154 would need complimentary legislation to become effective. One such confusing article limited `` real'' interest rates to 12 percent though no one knows what `` real'' interest rates in inflation-ridden <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> are. Inflation in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> is averaging more than 350 percent over the last 12 months. One of the most controversial articles fought over by legislators, who shouted each other down in day-long debates and often resorted to physical violence, set presidential elections in November 1989. Brazilians have n't voted for president since 1960. Representatives from 21 Latin American and Portuguese-speaking nations watched legislators enact <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>'s eighth constitution since the country gained independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1822.
</TEXT>
