<HEAD>Organizers Reject Criticism of Debate Staging as `Nonsense'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES to show debate held, new material; DELETES outdated
material.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE GLOVER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Organizers scorned criticism of the staging of Wednesday night's debate between <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> and <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> as `` a lot of nonsense'' which ignores the reality that the event is essentially a television show. <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON>, executive producer of the 90-minute confrontation between the two vice presidential candidates, says it's his business to fret about such seemingly trivial details as camera angles and the height of lecterns on the stage of the Omaha Civic Auditorium. `` This is a television program, and we've got some of the best production people in the world doing it,'' <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON> said. Sharing <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON>'s concerns are the Democratic and Republican contenders' campaign managers, who were eager to exploit the TV format to best advantage. In the past week of mock debates and briefings for the candidates, the medium was truly the message. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, for example, who is accustomed to the leisurely pace of <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> debate, spent days struggling _ with limited success _ to distill his debating points into those punchy, quotable `` sound bites'' that TV demands. About an hour into their debate, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> unleashed what he had learned. When <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> summoned up the name of former President <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> stared and him and said sternly: `` You're no <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>.'' The two warmed up with mild-by-comparison jabs over campaign finances, but in general the two candidates stuck to carefully scripted performances from the moment they strode onto the red, white and blue decorated stage. <PERSON> Mike </PERSON> <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON>, press secretary for the 67-year-old <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senator from <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said before the debate that <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> was having trouble observing the strict time limits specified for the debate _ two-minute answers to questions and one-minute rebuttals. `` The red light goes off frequently,'' <PERSON> McCurry </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, 41, seems more comfortable in a TV setting, has been coached by <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s media mastermind, <PERSON> Roger </PERSON> <PERSON> Ailes </PERSON>. Deflecting reporters' questions about his debate strategy, the <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION> senator said confidently that they should `` tune in and find out.'' During the debate, <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> stood casually with one foot propped on the podium, his face occasionally tightening when the audience laughed at a defense of his environmental record and during several tough questions tossed at him by panelists. The League of Women Voters withdrew as sponsors of the second scheduled debate between <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and Democratic nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> in mid-October, complaining that campaign strategists had turned the event into a `` charade'' by grabbing tight control of the mechanics of TV coverage. <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON> told reporters that restrictions demanded by the two campaigns were minor. He said the biggest was the decision not to show the audience of 2,000 people in the hall during the debate, except for fuzzy, `` over the shoulder'' shots. ` A lot of nonsense has been spoken and written about the shots,'' <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON> said. `` That's simply wrong. You direct a television program so people watching at home have a good idea what's happening. <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON>, executive director of the bipartisan debate commission sponsoring the Quayle-Bentsen clash, said it's natural that both sides will fight hard for any advantage in a closely fought presidential race. ` I'm very pleased with all the arrangements,'' Ms. <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> said. `` It's been a helpful exchange, a productive exchange, it's been a very honest exchange from all three parties.'' <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON> noted that the first Bush-Dukakis debate on Sept. 25 was viewed by an estimated 35 million households. He said details of the staging are crucial because `` millions of people are going to watch this debate on television.'' The intense interest in this year's campaign has put the smallest details of the debates under scrutiny. Debate rules, for example, allow only a three-inch variation in the height of the candidates' lecterns. The final decision is made after each candidate makes his allotted one-hour visit to the hall, closed to reporters, a few hours before the debate begins. Little appearing on camera has been left to chance. Even the journalists on the debate panel _ <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Brokaw </PERSON>, <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Margolis </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tribune </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> ABC </ORGANIZATION>'s <PERSON> Britt </PERSON> <PERSON> Hume </PERSON> _ drew lots to determine the order in which they asked questions. <PERSON> Fouhy </PERSON> said moderator <PERSON> Judy </PERSON> <PERSON> Woodruff </PERSON> of public broadcasting's <ORGANIZATION> MacNeil </ORGANIZATION> @ Lehrer NewsHour will use gentle persuasion rather than cutting off the microphones of any candidate who talks beyond his time limit Though the main floor of the Civic Auditorium was turned into a large TV studio for the debate, the scene was much more informal one level below, where most of the 1,500 reporters covering the debate could watch on TV monitors.
