<HEAD>Dukakis Assails Bush On Furloughs; Says Campaign Turning His Way</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf pvs, `The Democratic,' with 5 grafs new to
UPDATE with Dukakis comment on the debate; picks up 3rd graf pvs,
`Our campaign.'</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Debate Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> on Wednesday accused <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> of politically exploiting one `` tragic'' case involving a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> furlough program, said campaign momentum has shifted to him and promised `` five long, tough, aggressive weeks'' up to the election. The Democratic presidential nominee also praised the performance of his running mate, <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, in the vice presidential nominee's debate Wednesday night with Republican <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>. `` The most important qualification for the vice president is that he's ready at a moment's notice to assume the presidency of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told a rowdy rally with supporters shortly after the debate. `` Tonight <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> demonstrated that he was the only one on that stage who's ready.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who spoke to <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> immediately after the debate, said the Democrat's performance should tell the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people `` about how I make presidential decisions and the way <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> makes presidential decisions.'' `` Tonight that was no contest,'' he said. Earlier, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> used the debate to joke about the beginning of the American League playoff series between the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Oakland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Athletics </ORGANIZATION>. `` Our campaign is picking up steam,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> told a news conference at the <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Statehouse </LOCATION>, where he spent a day off the campaign trail catching up on gubernatorial duties. `` You can sense it. You can feel it. And I think it's because the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people want to move forward.'' Republican nominee <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has made his criticism of a <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION> furlough program a staple of his campaign and on Wednesday night aired a new television ad accusing <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> of running a `` revolving door'' prison system. At the center of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s attacks is a case in which an inmate on furlough raped a <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION> woman and assaulted her fiance <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, who earlier this year signed legislation tightening eligibility requirements for the program, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was exploiting that case despite a comparable federal program. `` The vice president's record on crime and the fight against drugs is pathetic,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` It's been a failure and in my judgment this is an effort to use the one case with a tragic occurrence for political reasons. The vice president knows that the federal government has a very extensive furlough program, knows that Governor <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> in the 70s had a very extensive furlough program and tragedies as a result of that.'' That answer came in response a question about suggestions by <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> Democrats that <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> was trailing in that key state despite have a Texan running mate because he had not responded forcefully enough to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s attacks on crime, gun control and other issues. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> promised he would return the salvos soon, and aides said they would come as soon as Thursday, when <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> planned to visit <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> with <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>. `` We have five, long, tough, aggressive weeks to go and believe me we'll be tough and aggressive in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and across this country and I think we're going to beat them in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> also defended his new ads portraying <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as an issue-less candidate controlled by advisers. `` I wanted to express the very strong feeling that I have and that I think many have that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> campaign is essentially a packaged candidacy and it's important for people to understand that,'' said <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. A new set of 30-second ads to be aired nationally starting Wednesday made a more direct attack on <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and his record on drug enforcement, education, the environment and Social Security. The four ads said the administration dealt secretly with <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON>, `` the Panamanian drug lord,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> `` personally'' weakened environmental regulations, `` personally'' cast the tie-breaking vote to cut Social Security'' and `` sat by while college loans for working families were cut.'' The governor also rejected assertions by a former Iranian official that the Democratic nominee had an emissary seeking to establish a line of communication with <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> and said he hoped the former official's assertion that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had an aide involved in hostage negotiations was untrue. `` I would hope that, and I believe, that these efforts to release the hostages have nothing to do with this campaign,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said. `` These families and these hostages have been through too much pain and too much agony and too much tragedy as it is. ... Certainly nobody representing me or someone authorized by me is engaged in those kind of discussions.'' As for the debate, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> opened his news conference by saying it was a day `` that we've been waiting a long time for.'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>, seemingly discussing the debate, said he was `` a little nervous'' and that he had been told by aides to try to lower expectations. `` I'm rejecting the advice of my staff,'' <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said as reporters leaned forward for his prediction. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> are going to win.'' His prediction proved wrong. The <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Sox </ORGANIZATION> lost 2-1. On a more serious note, <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> said he expected <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> to `` do himself and the Democratic ticket proud.''
