<FIRST>a p AM-Election-FatCats ADV10   10-05 0877</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Election-Fat Cats, ADV 10,0898</SECOND>
<NOTE>$Adv10</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, Oct. 10, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Campaign '88: Parties' Fat Cats Are Back and Spending Big</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RITA BEAMISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Despite Watergate-inspired curbs on election spending, millions of dollars are pouring into <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> and Democratic campaign treasuries from fat cat contributors this fall, and it's all legal. Documents made available to reporters recently show that both political parties are avidly courting the kind of big-money donations that were tarnished by revelations of Watergate-era abuses and then supposedly curtailed by election law reforms of the 1970s. The biggest Republican contributor is <PERSON> Nicholas </PERSON> <PERSON> Salgo </PERSON>, former <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador to <LOCATION> Hungary </LOCATION>, who was listed as giving more than $ 500,000 to his party. The Democrats say a couple of unidentified unions are giving $ 200,000 each. Both parties are going after individuals willing to give $ 100,000 or more. The <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> claims it has 115 such givers so far in the 1988 campaign. The <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> counts 100 fat cats, with a goal of doubling the number. These funds are known as `` soft money'' because federal law prohibits unions and corporations from making direct contributions to federal election campaigns, and limits individuals to giving $ 1,000 in presidential primaries only. In the general election, the presidential nominees are forbidden to accept any private donations because each receives $ 46.1 million from a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> fund supported by the voluntary $ 1 checkoff on individual income tax returns, plus $ 8.3 million from his party. So millions of dollars in soft money are funneled through the parties to finance political activities at the state and local level, which are not subject to federal regulation. Even at that level, the parties have no trouble finding ways to use soft money for activities, such as voter registration and TV commercials, that clearly benefit their presidential candidates. `` What is happening in 1988 is, it's becoming clearer and clearer -LRB- that -RRB- soft money is making a joke of the campaign finance laws,'' said <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> For </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Responsive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Politics </ORGANIZATION>, a research organization that advocates tightening campaign finance laws. The list of soft money receipts released by the Democrats, which covers only June and July, included $ 4.8 million of about $ 15 million the party has raised in soft money so far. No public accounting of soft money is required, and the Democrats say they will make no further fund-raising disclosures until after the Nov. 8 elections. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Farmer </PERSON>, fund-raising chief for <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> nominee <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> and head of the `` Victory Fund,'' says the party has a $ 50 million goal this year, with about $ 20 million coming from big-spending individuals. The GOP files showed $ 10 million in soft money raised through mid-September but did not include details of an additional $ 16 million raised by a `` Victory 88'' operation and slated for separate accounts in each state. Party officials say the Victory 88 goal is to raise $ 25 million in the states, while another soft money program, `` Team 100,'' will bring in about $ 15 million. Vice President <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, the Republican nominee, frequently attends glittery fund-raising events in banquet halls or private homes to help bolster the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION>'s `` Victory'88'' effort. Farmer mines the telephone network of wealthy Democratic donors and concentrates on big-ticket galas featuring <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>. While raising millions of dollars in soft money, the two major parties are stretching the rules to the limit. But they nonetheless are acting legally under guidelines which the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Election </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> is under court order to tighten up. Despite the federal ban on direct contributions to the candidates, party officials make support for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> or <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> a big part of their pitch to potential donors. `` We make it quite clear that they are not contributing to <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON>,'' said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Sweitzer </PERSON>, finance director for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. `` <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> is on the Democratic ticket and therefore he benefits indirectly from these funds. They're inspired by the head of the ticket to support the entire ticket.'' <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> developer <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Zappala </PERSON>, co-chairman of Republicans' Team 100 group of $ 100,000 donors, said that `` when you talk about <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, people are fairly receptive.'' <PERSON> Zappala </PERSON>'s tactic goes like this: `` You apprise people of the cost to run an election. It's expensive. We tell them we are running behind in fund raising. We do n't want to lose an election because we are running out of money.'' The Democrats, traditionally the fund-raising underdogs, say they have collected $ 38 million toward their $ 50 million goal this year. Of that sum, <PERSON> Sweitzer </PERSON> said, about $ 15 million is in soft money. Contrary to the ominous warnings in <PERSON> Zappala </PERSON>'s pitch, the <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> boasts $ 67 million in overall receipts so far this year. Of that total, $ 13 million is soft money being raised in state accounts toward a goal of $ 25 million, plus nearly $ 10 million that has come from fat cat donors, pricey galas and the party's `` Eagle'' program of $ 10,000-per-year givers Both parties say it's not easy persuading individuals to give $ 100,000 or more, but there seem to be plenty of willing donors. `` People are surprised they can give that much,'' <PERSON> Zappala </PERSON> said. `` There's been a lot of concerns about the federal legal limits. We explain to them it is legal.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, Oct. 10</NOTE>
