 The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> narrowly has sustained President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s veto of a bill that would have tightened curbs on imports of textiles and apparel. The <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> on Tuesday fell 11 votes short of the two-thirds necessary to override the veto and turn the bill into law. Supporters said the measure would save jobs, but opponents said it would mean price increases amounting to a fresh tax on consumers. The bill would have frozen 1988 textile, non-rubber footwear and apparel imports at last year's level. It would have allowed a 1 percent annual increase in imports of footwear and apparel beginning in January.
