<FIRST>r f PM-OilPrices     10-05 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Oil Prices,0359</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Steady, But Outlook Remains Bearish</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Analysts say the outlook for crude oil futures prices remains negative, despite recent stability. The November contract for <ORGANIZATION> West </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intermediate </ORGANIZATION>, the benchmark <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude, rose 1 cent Tuesday to settle at $ 13.07 a barrel on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The contract skidded 86 cents over Friday and Monday to $ 13.06 a barrel, the lowest close for a near-term WTI contract since August 1986. Concerns about oversupply of crude have brought prices down by about $ 2 a barrel over the past five weeks. Those concerns were heightened Monday by <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>'s threat to step up its crude output unless other members of the <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Petroleum </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exporting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Countries </ORGANIZATION> abide by their <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production quotas. Oil prices opened higher Tuesday amid rumors that <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> would move its ministerial meeting, scheduled for November, up to later this month, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Azarow </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> Shearson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lehman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hutton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. An early meeting raises speculation over the prospect of an agreement among <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> members to rein in the cartel's production But the rally, which analysts said was based on technical factors, soon ran out of steam. The November crude contract went as high as $ 13.30 a barrel before slipping back. `` We're still in a bear market,'' said <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON>, a trader with <ORGANIZATION> E.D. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> F. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Man </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> `` The market was expecting a rally of up to the $ 13.70 level and they have n't been able to get it.'' Besides <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> rumors, there was no news to affect trading, analysts said. `` The main thing goes back to the concerns about the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> overproduction,'' <PERSON> Fiedler </PERSON> said. Among refined products traded on the <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the November contract for wholesale unleaded gasoline fell 0.87 cent to 41.11 cents a gallon, while home heating oil rose 0.39 cent to 38.17 cents a gallon. <PERSON> Azarow </PERSON> said some of the movement in refined products was due to seasonal factors, such as a decline in driving that lowers demand for gas and the onset of cooler weather that increases heating oil use.
</TEXT>
