<FIRST>u f PM-Kroger Bjt   10-05 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kroger, Bjt,0676</SECOND>
<HEAD>Kohlberg Raises Offer for Supermarket Chain to $5.03 Billion</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Lede prospects uncertain.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BILL MENEZES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Roberts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> has n't yet launched a formal hostile takeover of <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, but in sweetening its buyout proposal for the supermarket giant it has outlined plans to keep stepping up the buyout pressure. <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> late Tuesday offered to pay $ 64 a share in cash and securities for each of <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>'s 78.6 million outstanding shares, an indicated total of $ 5.03 billion, and repeated its request to meet with the <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> board. The amount of the latest proposal topped not only the buyout firm's previous offer of $ 58.50 a share, or about $ 4.6 billion, but also the proposed $ 4.6 billion restructuring plan that <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>'s board of directors approved last month to thwart any outside takeover Furthermore, <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> indicated that if <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> decided to go through with the restructuring, the firm was willing to buy the surviving company _ and it hinted <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> also might be willing to take its offer directly to <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> shareholders. `` We have come forth with what we believe is an exceptional offer for your company's shareholders and we are confident that, if given the opportunity, your shareholders would embrace it,'' <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> said in a letter to the board of Cincinnati-based <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> announced its sweetened offer after the close of stock trading Tuesday in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> shares dipped 87 -LCB- cents to $ 55.37 -LCB- a share in heavy trading on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Company </ORGANIZATION>'s management, legal and financial advisers are reviewing the second unsolicited proposal from <ORGANIZATION> KKR </ORGANIZATION>,'' <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Bernish </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>, said late Tuesday. He said the company had no further comment. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> has been resisting overtures from <LOCATION> Kohlberg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kravis </LOCATION> and the <PERSON> Haft </PERSON> family of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, which had offered $ 4.32 billion, or $ 55 a share, for <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> specializes in leveraged buyouts _ purchases made with mostly borrowed money that is repaid with funds from the target company's operations or the sale of its assets. The firm rarely has engaged in an outright hostile takeover, partly because the success of its deals often depends on having existing management remain with the target company. But as its coffers have bulged with money from investors anxious to participate in buyouts _ <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> has an estimated $ 5.6 billion warchest that can be used as equity to leverage about seven times that amount _ pressure has mounted for the firm to be more aggressive in creating deals. <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION>' sweetened offer includes $ 50 in cash, $ 11 in debt securities and $ 3 in stock of the new company that <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kravis </ORGANIZATION> would create from <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>. The investment firm's earlier offer contained the same cash portion of $ 50 but only $ 8.50 in securities. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>'s restructuring announced Sept. 13 would pay stockholders a special dividend of $ 40 a share in cash, securities valued at $ 8 plus stock in the surviving company, valued at $ 5 to $ 10 a share. <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> <PERSON> Kravis </PERSON> said that if <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> undertook the plan, <PERSON> Kohlberg </PERSON> would be willing to acquire the stock in the restructured company for $ 13.50 a share _ $ 10 in cash and $ 3.50 a share in debentures. As such, <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> stockholders would realize a total of $ 61.50 a share in cash and securities from both parties. The investment firm noted the alternative, post-retructuring buyout would be for $ 2.50 a share less than its up-front offer, and said the difference reflected its estimates of financing fees <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> would have to pay under the restructuring plan, plus <ORGANIZATION> Kohlberg </ORGANIZATION>'s added costs in financing <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> debt incurred in the restructuring. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION>'s restructuring also includes layoffs and the sale of operations, in order to streamline the company and cut costs. <ORGANIZATION> Kroger </ORGANIZATION> operates more than 1,300 supermarkets, 935 convenience stores and 15 membership warehouses in 29 states. The company also processes food products for sale in its stores and to outside customers.
</TEXT>
