<HEAD>Pillsbury Fighting Takeover Bid From Britain's Grand Met</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In launching a $ 5.17 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Grand </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metropolitan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION> is proposing to strip <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> of a division that has helped make the company vulnerable to a takeover. Grand Metropolitan said in a filing with the <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> that if its $ 60-a-share bid begun Tuesday succeeds, it would sell <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Steak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ale and <ORGANIZATION> Bennigan </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> restaurant operations The under-performing full-service restaurant division was restructured in January, resulting in a $ 91 million charge that has dragged down earnings. The restructuring also precipitated management changes, including the hiring of former <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foods </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> chairman <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> as its own new chairman in July. Grand Metropolitan indicated it would sell <ORGANIZATION> Steak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; Ale and <PERSON> Bennigan </PERSON>'s because of state laws prohibiting a company from owning both alcoholic beverage makers and retailers. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> is using that issue to challenge the takeover bid, although by Tuesday it had not actually or approved of the offer. In a statement issued late Tuesday, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> had sued to block the acquisition in 13 states, contending a buyout by Grand Met would violate liquor laws prohibiting producers from owning liquor retailers. Courts in <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Michigan </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pennsylvania </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Missouri </LOCATION> have issued temporary restraining orders enjoining Grand Met from acquiring any <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> stock, and a <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION> court has rejected Grand Met's effort to stop those actions, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> said. Grand Met, a $ 10 billion a year diversified company, is one of the world's biggest wine and spirit makers, with brands that include <ORGANIZATION> Smirnoff </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Vodka </ORGANIZATION>, J & amp; B Scotch, <PERSON> Gilbey </PERSON>'s Gin, <PERSON> Watney </PERSON> and Ushers ale and Almaden wines. In a separate statement, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> said that its board would review the offer `` at an appropriate time.'' <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said at the company's annual shareholders' meeting in September that one of his chief goals was keeping the company independent. But on Tuesday, industry analysts doubted <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> could defend itself against the takeover bid and remain independent. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> stock soared by $ 18.50 a share to $ 57.50 on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> Tuesday, the first trading session after Grand Met made its offer. `` It's going to be a bid that <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> management is going to have difficulty defending against,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> McMillen </PERSON>, an analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Prudential-Bache </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Securities </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. `` I think they'll fight it initially _ attempt to fight it _ but I think it's a losing battle. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, Grand Metropolitan's chief executive for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operations, said Tuesday in <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> that he is `` very interested in doing this thing in a gentlemanly manner.'' <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s struggling restaurant division, which includes the Burger King fast-food chain, provides about half <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 6.2 billion in annual revenue. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said Grand Metropolitan would keep Burger King but would sell <PERSON> Distron </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s in-house distribution system for Burger King. London-based Grand Metropolitan also owns hotels, the Alpo pet food company, <ORGANIZATION> Pearle </ORGANIZATION> vision centers, and a chain of betting offices in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>. Analysts speculated Grand Metropolitan was most interested in <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> for its <ORGANIZATION> Green </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Giant </ORGANIZATION> vegetable, Haagen-Dazs ice cream and <PERSON> Van </PERSON> <PERSON> de </PERSON> <PERSON> Kamp </PERSON>'s frozen fish operations. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> said there were good prospects for marketing <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s food products overseas, especially its microwavable foods Further, Grand Metropolitan proposed in a letter to <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> that <LOCATION> Minneapolis </LOCATION> become the headquarters of a Grand Met international foods group. <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, who met with a number of state officials while waiting for a response from <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, said Grand Metropolitan decided to move aggressively with a tender offer because <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> officials had indicated that `` if anyone came near the drawbridge, they would have a real cat-and-dog fight.'' Grand Metropolitan filed suit on Monday in <ORGANIZATION> Delaware </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chancery </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> to invalidate <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>'s `` poison pill'' takeover defense, which would make a hostile merger prohibitively expensive. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> is incorporated in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> also might seek protection from <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> lawmakers, who met in special session last year to pass legislation protecting Minneapolis-based <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> from a possible hostile takeover bid by the <PERSON> Haft </PERSON> family.
