<HEAD>Network To Offer Buyouts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARJORIE ANDERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> says it will offer buyouts to as many as 140 engineers and technicians in an effort to trim at least 40 employees from its work force. <PERSON> Dom </PERSON> <PERSON> Giofre </PERSON>, a spokesman for the television network, said the buyout offer was prompted by the recent sale of <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION>'s radio operation and by the winding down of 1988 political coverage. `` I do n't think this really comes as a real surprise to anyone,'' said <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Sherlock </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> President of Operations and Technical Services. He said only employees in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> are involved. <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> has has dramatically reduced its payroll since it was acquired by <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> two years ago. About 400 people in the news division have lost their jobs and another 110 are scheduled to go before the end of the year. The engineers and technicians were scheduled to be notified beginning today in a series of meetings with supervisors. `` If all 140 people accept, they will pay it, although they are aiming to cut only 40 positions,'' said <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> McElroy </PERSON>, a spokesman for Local 11 of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Employees </ORGANIZATION> and Technicians. Workers will have until Nov. 10 to accept the voluntary offer. Those who accept will continue to receive regular paychecks as well as health and other benefits through the end of the year. The balance of the severance would be paid in a lump sum on Jan. 2, <PERSON> Sherlock </PERSON> said. Currently, <ORGANIZATION> NBC </ORGANIZATION> employs about 1,000 technicians, down by 300 since a 118-day strike in 1987.
