<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0011,0588</SECOND>
<HEAD>15.6 Million Vehicles Sold in '88: Third Best in History</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 9th graf, Ford Motor ..., to CORRECT Ford sales this
year to 2.14 million, sted 2.4 million, add more precise Chrysler
totals. Picks up 10th graf pvs, Overall sales ...</NOTE>
<HEAD>With PM-Auto Sales-Table</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s growing love affair with light trucks towed the auto industry to its third-best year on record, as car makers reported selling 15.6 million vehicles in the 1988 model year. The 0.7 percent increase over the 15.5 million vehicles sold during the 1987 model year was fattened by strong sales of U.S.-made light trucks, including pickups, minivans and sports utility vehicles. The overall increase came despite a slight dip in sales of cars, the automakers reported Tuesday. Foreign and domestic car makers reported car sales slipped 1.4 percent to about 10.4 million cars in the model year ended last Friday from about 10.5 million cars sold during the year before. But sales of light trucks rose 4.2 percent to 5.1 million in 1988, from 4.9 million in the 1987 model year. Leading the way were U.S.-made trucks, rising to 4.4 million vehicles this year, compared just less than 4 million last year, an 11.2 percent increase. Sales of light trucks made outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> tumbled 24.9 percent to 724,584 vehicles in the 1988 model year from 961,465 in the year before. `` There has been a lot of competition for trucks on the domestic and foreign side,'' said <PERSON> Jeannette </PERSON> <PERSON> Garretty </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION>. `` That has ... given the appearance and the actuality that you can swing a good deal in that market.'' But overall car sales have drooped. Industry leader <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> was the only loser among the Big Three in the 1988 model year, with sales of about 3.6 million U.S.-made cars between Oct. 1, 1987 and Sept. 30, 1988, down 4.9 percent from the 3,719,267 domestically made cars it sold the year before. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s sales rose 2.9 percent to 2.14 million cars in 1988 from 2.07 million in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> sales rose 3 percent to about 1.05 million cars in 1988 from 1.01 million during the year before. Overall sales made it a stronger-than-expected model year, which analysts had anticipated would see sales of about 15 million vehicles or less. `` I think it's particularly surprising in light of what the initial expectations were post-Oct. 19 of last year'' when the stock market crashed, said analyst <PERSON> Douglas </PERSON> <PERSON> Laughlin </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Bear </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stearns </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> `` I was looking more for 14 million in that period. I had to consistently raise it through the period,'' he said. The model year ended on a downturn for the automakers as September sales of imported cars and trucks fell to 268,362 vehicles, down 16.6 percent from the 321,656 vehicles sold during the same month last year. Sales of U.S.-made cars and trucks dipped 2.2 percent in September, to 895,861 vehicles from 916,410 vehicles during September 1987. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> showed the largest car sales decline in the Sept. 21-30 period, dropping 15 percent to 116,028 cars this year from 136,483 during the same period last year. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>'s late September sales fell to 70,813 cars, down 14.3 percent from 82,606 during the period last year. <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>'s late-September sales dropped 4.5 percent to 33,314 cars this year from 34,898 last year.
</TEXT>
