<HEAD>McKesson Drops Plans to Acquire Alco, Northwestern</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> McKesson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest drug distributor, has called off its proposed acquisition of <ORGANIZATION> Alco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's third largest drug wholesaler. In Tuesday's announcement, the companies sited a decision by the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> to move to block the merger. <ORGANIZATION> McKesson </ORGANIZATION> offered $ 500 million in June for Alco, based in <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Forge </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, and extended the offer five times when the companies could n't agree on the price. The <ORGANIZATION> FTC </ORGANIZATION> on Monday authorized its staff to seek a preliminary injunction against the plan. <ORGANIZATION> McKesson </ORGANIZATION> also said on Tuesday it will abandon plans to buy <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Auburn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> McKesson </ORGANIZATION> offered about $ 200 million for the drug wholesaler The <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Retail </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Druggists </ORGANIZATION> contends the <ORGANIZATION> McKesson-Alco </ORGANIZATION> merger would give the companies 50 percent of the drug distribution market in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, according to <PERSON> Tim </PERSON> <PERSON> Feagans </PERSON>, an attorney for Alco. The commission said both the acquisition of <LOCATION> Alco </LOCATION> and Northwestern could significantly reduce competition.
