<FILEID>AP-NR-10-05-88 2337EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f PM-OntheMoney Adv06   10-05 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-On the Money, Adv 06,0666</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv 06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday Oct 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>Choices Proliferate in CDs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Now that such former best sellers as stocks and mutual funds have fallen out of favor, financial institutions are busy these days pushing a hot new idea _ certificates of deposit. Not just plain vanilla CDs, mind you, though you can certainly still get those stodgy old-timers if you want them. What we're dealing with now are rising-rate CDs, floating-rate CDs, CDs with no set maturity dates, even CDs that effectively let you make a legal bet on your favorite sports team or the outcome of the November election. All this has n't happened just by chance. The stock market crash last fall and the wide swings in interest rates over the past several years have brought big changes in the marketplace where brokers and bankers sell their merchandise. `` I choose to think of it as a rebirth of investor prudence,'' says <PERSON> William </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, a Valley Forge, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, adviser on tax and investment planning.'' `` Today's low tax rates and market turmoil have reinstated preservation of principal as a justifiable objective for personal planning.'' In this environment, CDs are a natural choice for financial marketers to seize upon. Thanks to today's high level of real interest rates -LRB- as compared with the inflation rate -RRB-, they can offer a reasonable return, with the backing of federal deposit insurance. And thanks to financial deregulation, the once-rigid format of a certificate of deposit has become very flexible. In general, financial advisers say, that is a plus for savers and investors. But they caution that it takes a lot of care to distinguish the substance from the sizzle in the new generation of CDs. There is no real harm, for instance, in buying a CD whose yield will vary depending on the outcome of the Super Bowl or the election, as long as you have enough financial leeway to play that kind of game with your money. A little no-nonsense calculation may cool your enthusiasm for such a deal, which do n't really offer much of a payout or loss. With one `` presidential'' CD now on the market, the newsletter 100 Highest Yield calculates, if the candidate of your choice wins with 59 percent of the popular vote -LRB- the amount President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> got in his 1984 landslide -RRB-, you would receive an extra $ 10.13 over the next four years on a $ 1,000 deposit. If you opt to shop purely for yield and safety, the choices are still bewilderingly large. Newsletters like 100 Highest Yields, in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Palm </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, and Income & amp; Safety, in <LOCATION> Fort </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Lauderdale </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, compile lists of top-yielding CD offerings by banks and savings institutions around the country. Even with federal deposit insurance, it makes sense these days to check out the status and prospects of some faraway institution before you mail off a large deposit check. Alternatively, you can do your CD shopping at brokerage firms, which may have certificates from a wide variety of insured institutions to offer. `` Brokerage houses not only seek out the highest-paying institutions to provide CDs for their customers, but they also frequently negotiate special package deals that lead to higher rates than the same banks offer directly to the public,'' says the Income & amp; Safety newsletter. It may be possible to liquidate a CD investment bought from a broker before maturity without paying a penalty, since most brokers endeavor to maintain a continuous `` secondary'' market in the CDs they sell. You probably wo n't have to pay a commission when you buy or sell. But if you are thinking of selling before maturity, check into the `` spread'' _ the difference between the broker's bid and asked prices. Just possibly, the spread might be as large as or larger than the early withdrawal penalty.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thurs Oct 6</NOTE>
