<FIRST>a f PM-BusinessMirror Adv06   10-05 0544</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 06 ,0558</SECOND>
<NOTE>$adv06</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release PMs Thursday, Oct. 6</NOTE>
<HEAD>Measuring The Quality of Service</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN CUNNIFF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Analyst</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Asked in a survey to name five companies they associate with quality products, 1,005 Americans most often named <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> IBM </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>. Nothing really surprising in that, or in the second five _ <ORGANIZATION> AT </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> T </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Sony </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION>, RCA -LRB- a GE subsidiary -RRB- and <ORGANIZATION> Procter </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Gamble </ORGANIZATION> _ because they would n't be so big unless they were doing something right. What is surprising is that the characteristic most often cited in determining product quality is how well the name is known, outranking such considerations as workmanship, price, performance, durability and style. The response to a Gallup survey for the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Quality </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> suggests how difficult it is to evaluate the mind of the American consumer in dealing with manufactured products. But if it is difficult to measure attitudes toward the most tangible of products, it is even more so in dealing with services, which are produced in even greater abundance in the American economy. How, for example, do you measure the quality of an insurance policy when you do not even understand its contents? You know when an automobile runs well; you might never know how well your policy performs until you have an accident. Cost comparisons are more difficult too. Some life insurance policies actually provide better coverage and higher cash value at a lower price than others. But only geniuses or actuaries are likely to know the difference. As a result, the perception of service quality is more likely to be on the basis of interaction with specific individuals, such as insurance agents. Price for example, ranked sixth as a service quality determinant in the Gallup poll, behind `` courteous, polite treatment,'' the satisfaction of needs, past experience, recommendations and promptness. High on the list were such determinants as attitude and helpfulness of personnel, friendliness and personal atttention. Far down the list was `` company name,'' a factor that seemed to play a large role in rating product quality. Unlike the product quality survey, Gallup did n't rate individual companies in a survey on service. Instead, it limited responses to perceptions of quality in segments of the service industry, with these results: On a scale of 1 to 10, or worst to highest, banks received the highest evaluation, with a 54 percent majority ranking their service at 8 or better. It was the only one to exceed 50 percent. Ranked second were hotels, at 44 percent, followed by hospitals, airlines and insurance companies -LRB- a tie -RRB-, automobile repairs and local government. Compared with a similar survey in 1985, banks, hotels, auto repairs and local government services improved. Insurance companies, hospitals and airlines fell. Featured on the down list were airlines, which provoked the observation from the Gallup folks that `` since 1985, the one service which experienced the greatest decrease in high quality ratings is the airlines.'' For the airlines it was the equivalent of a downdraft. In the 1985 survey, 47 percent of those interviewed perceived airline quality as rating no lower than an 8 on the 10-level scale. In 1988, only 32 percent rated airlines that high.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Thursday, Oct. 6</NOTE>
