<HEAD>Union Carbide Sues Seven Japanese Companies</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>'s legal charges that seven Japanese companies manipulated the price of a raw material for computer chips are `` utterly baseless,'' one of the defendants claims. Union Carbide sued Monday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION>, asking for a jury trial and an order prohibiting the seven from fixing prices and controlling the export to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> of polysilicon, the raw material for silicon wafers. The lawsuit seeks damages for the losses <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> suffered as a result of the alleged conspiracy. The defendants are <ORGANIZATION> Komatsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>; its parent firm, <ORGANIZATION> Komatsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Mitsubishi </ORGANIZATION> subsidiary <ORGANIZATION> Nippon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Silicon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Osaka </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Titanium </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Shinetsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Handotai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Tokuyama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Soda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. Ltd.. <ORGANIZATION> Komatsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Metals </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, together with its parent, <ORGANIZATION> Komatsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ltd. </ORGANIZATION>, issued a joint `` Although <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> calls it an antitrust suit, its complaint is really part of an ongoing contract dispute with <ORGANIZATION> KEM </ORGANIZATION>, arising out of <ORGANIZATION> UCC </ORGANIZATION>'s unfounded interpretation of its contract with <ORGANIZATION> KEM </ORGANIZATION>,'' it said. The statements said <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> is trying to recoup `` self-inflicted losses resulting from its own flawed business decisions at the expense of a Japanese company that has adhered fully to the letter and the spirit of its contractual obligations.'' The suit by <LOCATION> Danbury </LOCATION>, Conn.-based <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> claimed <ORGANIZATION> Komatsu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electronic </ORGANIZATION> and other companies that purchased the material and produced silicon wafers formed a `` polysilicon buyers' cartel'' in 1983. According to the lawsuit, the Japanese companies arranged to `` deplete inventories, to refrain from bidding against one another for fixed supplies in order to minimize open market price increases and otherwise set purchase prices.'' Union Carbide said several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> polysilicon manufacturers have been forced to exit the merchant market because of the defendants' action The defendants and other Japanese companies banded together and pose as a silicon-wafer industry study group. However, they secretly exchanged information about business costs, pricing, supply and demand and strategic plans to the detriment of non-Japanese companies, the suit said.
