<SECOND>BC-EEC-Patent Law,0131</SECOND>
<HEAD>EEC Urges Standardized Biotechnology Patent Laws</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday proposed EEC-wide patent legislation to protect biotechnology inventions in the 12-nation trade bloc. National patent laws differ so much from one <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> nation to the next that `` lack of legal certainty and lack of sufficient protection is commonplace in the Community in this field,'' the commission said. EEC scientists are at a disadvantage compared to their colleagues in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>, whose laws offer `` considerably more protection through patentability that is currently available in <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>,'' the commission said. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Patent </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trademark </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> has already granted a patent on a man-made mouse from <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is expected to grant similar patents shortly.
