<SECOND>AM-Drought Insurance,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Some Farmers Get Drought Insurance Checks; Others Battle Company</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Illinois farmers who received controversial drought insurance coverage have begun to receive payments, but for those involuntarily left without policies, the legal fight continues, officials said Wednesday. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>, assistant director of the state <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, said the <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> has mailed checks for more than $ 5 million to <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> farmers who received the insurance coverage. <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION>, a New Jersey-based insurance group, has estimated that 1,058 Illinois farmers applied for coverage but only 263 of them received drought insurance policies. Another 715 farmers accepted the company's double-premium refund offer. Agents in the drought-stricken <LOCATION> Cornbelt </LOCATION> advertised the insurance and accepted premium payments late this spring _ when many farmers already suspected it would be a very dry growing season. When underwriters realized that 10 times the $ 30 million intended issue had been sold, they raised the issue to $ 40 million and issued policies only if applications were made by June 15. Those who received insurance coverage were guaranteed payments if the rainfall in their counties from June through August was below certain levels. <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said most payments to <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> farmers are in the $ 8,000-20 ,000 range However, he said two farmers at <LOCATION> Sheldon </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Iroquois </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> received $ 128,000 and $ 177,000 respectively. <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> so far has made drought insurance payments to five farmers in <LOCATION> Ford </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, 29 in <LOCATION> Iroquois </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, 32 in <LOCATION> Kankakee </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION>, 54 in <LOCATION> Livingston </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> and one each in <LOCATION> Champaign </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> McLean </LOCATION> counties. But many other farmers still hope to receive the drought insurance they thought they purchased _ and the payments that would boost their income significantly. One farm family told the <LOCATION> Champaign-Urbana </LOCATION> News-Gazette that they paid an $ 18,000 premium but did not receive a policy. Instead, they said <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> refunded twice that amount as a `` goodwill'' gesture. However, the family said what they want is the insurance and the payment they would be due under the coverage _ more than $ 160,000. Farmers who paid premiums all over the country are party to a class-action suit in federal court in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> that seeks to force <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> to extend the coverage to anyone who paid a premium and still wants the insurance. The state <ORGANIZATION> Insurance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> is trying to determine how many <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION> farmers paid premiums and did not receive policies, so it can calculate how much <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION> would owe to farmers in the state. <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON> said his department then is likely to file charges against <ORGANIZATION> Chubb </ORGANIZATION>, focusing on the fact that the company did not clear the policy with state officials before offering it for sale. `` Our bottom-line interest is protecting state farmers and forcing the company to satisfy our farmers,'' said <PERSON> Carlson </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
