<FIRST>u f AM-Pillsbury     10-05 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pillsbury,0641</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Leaders Don't Fear Grand Metropolitan As They Did Dart</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED STYCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Grand Metropolitan PLC, the British company bidding to take over <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, is n't terrifying state officials, lawmakers and charitable organizations as <ORGANIZATION> Dart </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> did when it tried to seize <ORGANIZATION> Dayton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hudson </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> last year. `` I think it's certainly not a similar situation in many respects,'' <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Duane </PERSON> <PERSON> Benson </PERSON>, IR-Lanesboro, said Wednesday. `` It does n't appear to be a situation in which -LRB- Grand Metropolitan -RRB- may come into the community, plunder and leave when they're done.'' Both <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Dayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON> are Minneapolis-based companies that have earned favorite-son status for their high levels of charitable giving and general community do-gooding. Last year, Minnesotans were horrified when <PERSON> Dart </PERSON>, controlled by the <PERSON> Haft </PERSON> family of <LOCATION> Maryland </LOCATION>, tried to acquire <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> in a hostile takeover. The Hafts, with a reputation as corporate raiders who made millions from profits on the sale of stock acquired from companies they tried to take over, were considered poor corporate citizens. The <ORGANIZATION> Minnesota </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> rode to the rescue and swiftly acted on <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION>'s request to pass tough anti-takeover legislation in a one-day special session. But because <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> is incorporated in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, the new <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> anti-takeover laws offer no help to the food conglomerate. And, because Grand Metropolitan has quickly presented itself as a responsible company that would do little to upset the status quo, <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> said, the state may not be as hasty to help <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> as it was to help <PERSON> Dayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>. `` It's going to be tough to do for them -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, because they're incorporated in <LOCATION> Delaware </LOCATION>, not here,'' <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> said. `` It would have to be pretty specific legislation.'' House Speaker <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Vanasek </PERSON>, DFL-New <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION>, agreed. `` I'm not too excited about seeing a Minnesota-based company being taken over by one that's headquartered outside the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, but I do n't think there's really anything we could do about it,'' <PERSON> Vanasek </PERSON> said. Still, he said, `` The <PERSON> Dart </PERSON> group has a terrible reputation when it comes to being raiders, and at least Grand Met seems to be a pretty solid company.'' <PERSON> Vanasek </PERSON>, <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> and other state leaders, including Gov. <PERSON> Rudy </PERSON> <PERSON> Perpich </PERSON>, met with Grand Metropolitan officials Tuesday, the day they officially made their $ 5.17 billion bid for <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Martin </PERSON>, chief executive of Grand Metropolitan's <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> operations, who had asked for the meeting, said the company was n't seeking political favors, only a `` level playing field'' in dealing with <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> `` I thought after having gone through the whole <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> situation, this was strange,'' <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> said. `` It was a reversal. <PERSON> Dart </PERSON> certainly did n't come to talk to us.'' But <PERSON> Benson </PERSON> thought the presentation was helpful. `` I think it certainly gave us a chance to understand their point of view and what their attempts are,'' he said. `` I got the impression that they're not a corporate raider. If they're successful at taking <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> over, they'll keep that high community identity.'' State Commerce Commissioner <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said corporate takeovers have changed since the <LOCATION> Dayton </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hudson </LOCATION> deal. Now, companies like Grand Metropolitan quickly approach politicians and the news media to fend off negative publicity. `` What they -LRB- Grand Metropolitan -RRB- were trying to do was to communicate the sincerity of their offer and that they do have a background as a good corporate citizen,'' said <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON>, who also attended Tuesday's meeting. Not only has Grand Metropolitan handled the situation differently than <PERSON> Dart </PERSON>, <PERSON> Hatch </PERSON> said, but <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION> has handled it differently than <PERSON> Dayton </PERSON> <PERSON> Hudson </PERSON>, which acted immediately after <PERSON> Dart </PERSON> started its takeover attempt. <ORGANIZATION> Pillsbury </ORGANIZATION>, in a statement Tuesday, said its board would review the Grand Met offer `` at an appropriate time.'' Company officials refused to make further comment on Wednesday.
