<HEAD>General Dynamics Gets Smaller Sub Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday awarded the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> a $ 617.4 million contract for a new Trident missile submarine, slashing more than $ 26.6 million off the price it paid last year. <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> officials said the award demonstrated they had been right in pressing a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> shipyard to compete against <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> more than a year ago, even if <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> ultimately succeeded in protecting its monopoly on the huge subs. `` It shows the benefits of competition,'' said Lt. <PERSON> Ken </PERSON> <PERSON> Ross </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> spokesman. `` That previous competition ... is still bearing fruit.'' The contract awarded Wednesday represents the first of two options in a contract initially awarded by the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> in January after competitive bidding between <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Drydock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co </ORGANIZATION>. The award to <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Boat </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Groton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Conn. </LOCATION>, covers the one Trident submarine authorized by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> in the fiscal 1989 budget and will be the 16th in the line. The fixed-price contract specifies the Trident should be delivered by October 1994. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has said it wants to order at least 20 Tridents and possibly more. With the exception of nuclear-powered aircraft carriers, the Trident program was the last major <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> shipbuilding program to be opened to competition. <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipbuilding </ORGANIZATION>, a division of <ORGANIZATION> Tenneco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, enjoys a monopoly on the construction of aircraft carriers, in part because no other shipyard has the massive facilities required to build that type of ship. In November 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> accepted a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> request that it compete against <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> in the Trident program. It submitted a bid for the fiscal 1988 sub as well as option bids on the two additional boats expected to be purchased in fiscal 1989 and fiscal 1990. General Dynamics did the same, and last Jan. 5 the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> announced <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dynamics </ORGANIZATION> had succeeded in preserving its monopoly by underbidding <ORGANIZATION> Newport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> awarded the firm a $ 644 million contract for the fiscal 1988 submarine, without revealing what either company had bid for the two option years. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said Wednesday the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> believes it will save roughly $ 100 million over the life of the contract if the second option is also exercised. The spokesman said the latest award reverses what has been a spiraling price for the huge vessels. The fiscal 1986 submarine cost the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> about $ 587 million. The price climbed to $ 615 million in fiscal 1987, then rose again in January to $ 644 million. `` This contract is cutting more than $ 26 million off that fiscal 1988 buy,'' <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> said. The 560-foot Trident submarines _ also known as the <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> class _ are considered the most survivable leg of <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'s nuclear arsenal. Each of the vessels can carry 24 long-range, multi-warhead nuclear missiles and remain submerged for months at a time. Each of the subs, when completely outfitted with nuclear reactors and government-furnished equipment, cost more than $ 1.4 billion. Eight of the submarines are already commissioned on active duty and a ninth _ the USS Tennessee _ will soon join them.
