<HEAD>UNCTAD Chief Executive Welcomes Reaction To Reduction Proposals</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A senior <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> official said Wednesday he is pleased with the initial response from the international community to a proposal that commercial lenders write off 30 percent of their loans to 15 highly indebted Third World countries. But <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dadzie </PERSON>, Secretary General of the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Conference </ORGANIZATION> on Trade and Development, made clear that consensus on how to cope with the debt crisis is far away. In a press statement, however, he voiced confidence that the proposal, outlined in <ORGANIZATION> UNCTAD </ORGANIZATION>'s 1988 report last month, `` served as a catalyst for a rethinking of positions and will continue to do so.'' The countries targeted by the <ORGANIZATION> UNCTAD </ORGANIZATION> plan account for about 60 percent of Third World debt totaling some $ 500 billion. They are <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Bolivia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colombia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ivory </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ecuador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Peru </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Uruguay </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Venezuela </LOCATION>, and <LOCATION> Yugoslavia </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Dadzie </PERSON> said that while the plan called for 30-percent cut of commercial bank debt, `` our calculations can -LRB- perhaps -RRB- be improved in either and upoward or downward direction.'' He saiid it is increasingly obvious that large-scale debt reduction `` can not be accomplished by credit markets acting on their own'' but that it required concerted action by creditors. <PERSON> Dadzie </PERSON> said recent statements by <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> and the director oof the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Monetary </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund </ORGANIZATION> suggest `` that the need for official action is gaining acceptance.'' `` The form of the support, however, remains unclear,'' he added, speaking of a `` highly complex situation.'' <PERSON> Dadzie </PERSON>'s statement was issued at the end of a two-week session of <ORGANIZATION> UNCTAD </ORGANIZATION>'s 131-nation governing body, the Trade and <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>.
