<HEAD>Eastern Pilots Threaten To Block Reported Sale of Shuttle to Trump</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: INSERTS 2 new grafs after 5th graf pvs Texas Air... to UPDATE
with Trump comments to newspaper. Picks up 6th graf pvs, The
report...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Unions at <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> reacted angrily Wednesday to a report that <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> was discussing the possible sale of its <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> air shuttle to developer <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Trump </PERSON>. The pilots union warned it would seek a court order to block any such deal, and the head of the machinists union suggested his union would do the same. The unions successfully blocked an attempt earlier this year by <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> to transfer the shuttle operation from Eastern to a new subisidiary. According to unidentified sources quoted by the <ORGANIZATION> Wall </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Street </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Journal </ORGANIZATION>, the pricetag on the three-city shuttle was in the range of $ 200 million. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Mark </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON> said the company had no comment on the Journal report. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> and his representatives also declined comment. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION>, in its Thursday editions, quoted <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> as saying he was close to agreement on a deal, and a contract could be signed by next week. The newspaper also quoted unidentified executives it said were close to the deal as saying <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> would pay more than $ 300 million cash for the shuttle. <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> was dealing directly with <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lorenzo </PERSON> in the deal, the <ORGANIZATION> Times </ORGANIZATION> quoted its sources as saying. The report came a day after <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> signed an agreement with Scandinavian Airlines System giving the European carrier leases on airport gates in the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> area and the right to buy up to 10 percent of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>'s stock on the open market. <ORGANIZATION> SAS </ORGANIZATION> will pay <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> $ 50 million under the accord, which also includes provisions for coordinating marketing, reservations and scheduling as well as training of airline personnel. In <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> pilots union spokesman <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Cole </PERSON> said the union `` will take whatever steps are necessary to legally protect Eastern from the sale or transfer of any more of its assets.'' The leader of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union said <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> employees probably would challenge any sale of the shuttle. `` We stopped the spinoff to <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. It's something we will have to look at as it relates to our ongoing litigation,'' said <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bryan </PERSON>, head of the <ORGANIZATION> Machinists </ORGANIZATION> union at Eastern. The Machinists filed a federal suit earlier this year to block the plan to make <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s shuttle a separate subsidiary of <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> later dropped that effort. While stressing they did not know if the report was true, some Wall Street analysts said <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> might use the shuttle, which operates between <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, to help draw people to his hotel and casino properties in <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION> Others expressed skepticism. `` I think it makes some eminent sense,'' said <PERSON> Julius </PERSON> <PERSON> Maldutis </PERSON>, an airline analyst for <ORGANIZATION> Salomon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Brothers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>. One skeptic, <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Pincavage </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> PaineWebber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, suggested it would be difficult for <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> to revamp the shuttle to accommodate traffic to <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> The shuttle service, one of the most profitable operations of ailing <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>, is mainly geared toward business passengers. <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> would more likely sell aircraft or routes to raise cash, rather than a lucrative shuttle operation, <PERSON> Pincavage </PERSON> said. He suggested that discussions with <PERSON> Trump </PERSON> could be a way of putting a pricetag on the shuttle in case <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> declared bankruptcy and it had to be sold.
